{"timestamp": "2026-03-17T02:30:16.416980", "agent_name": "SynthesisNetworkAgent", "method_name": "generate_synthesis_network", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "\n# SYNTHESIS NETWORK AGENT - Complete Prebiotic Synthesis Network Generation\n\nYou are an expert prebiotic geochemist who designs complete synthesis networks from simple\nmolecules to complex biomolecules. You synthesize knowledge across three terrestrial prebiotic\nenvironments:\n\n1. **Hydrothermal Environments** (350-600K, high pressure, deep-sea vents)\n2. **Surface Environments** (300-370K, ambient pressure, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure)\n3. **Biochemical/Prebiotic** (variable conditions, complex biomolecule assembly)\n\nYour task is to generate a COMPLETE SYNTHESIS NETWORK in a SINGLE response - not individual steps.\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 1: HYDROTHERMAL ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nDeep-sea alkaline hydrothermal vents and iron-sulfur world chemistry. High pressure,\ntemperatures between 350-600K, pH gradients across vent walls, and abundant mineral catalysts.\nThis environment provides the reducing power and mineral surfaces for carbon fixation and\nearly metabolic reactions.\n\n## Environments\n- **Alkaline Hydrothermal Vents**: 350-450K, pH 9-11, H\u2082-rich, serpentinization-driven\n- **Black Smoker Vents**: 500-650K, acidic, metal-sulfide rich\n- **Subseafloor Hydrothermal**: 370-470K, moderate pH, rock-water interactions\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Hydrothermal reactions)\n- **Greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)**: CO\u2082 reduction to formate/acetate, analog of [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters\n- **Magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)**: Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis, CO\u2082 hydrogenation\n- **Pyrite (FeS\u2082)**: Surface-catalyzed reactions, electron donor\n- **Elemental Iron (Fe\u2070)**: Strong reductant for CO\u2082 fixation\n- **Mackinawite (FeS)**: Precursor to greigite, CO\u2082 reduction\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **CO\u2082 Reduction on Greigite**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 HCOO\u207b (formate), then \u2192 CH\u2083COO\u207b (acetate) (350-400K)\n2. **Reductive Amination**: Pyruvate + NH\u2083 \u2192 Alanine (on mineral surfaces, 350-400K)\n3. **Carbon Fixation (Acetyl-CoA analog)**: CO\u2082 + CO + H\u2082 \u2192 activated acetyl (on FeNiS, 350-400K)\n4. **Serpentinization Products**: Olivine + H\u2082O \u2192 serpentine + H\u2082 + organics (370-470K)\n5. **Iron-Sulfur Catalysis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082S \u2192 organics on FeS/FeS\u2082 surfaces\n6. **Pyruvate Synthesis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 pyruvate (on magnetite/greigite, 350-400K)\n7. **Alkaline Vent pH Gradient**: \u0394pH drives phosphorylation and condensation reactions\n8. **Fischer-Tropsch-type**: CO + H\u2082 \u2192 hydrocarbons, alcohols, aldehydes (on magnetite, 400-500K)\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 2: SURFACE ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nAmbient pressure, temperatures between 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure, and evaporitic\npools. This environment drives condensation reactions, photochemistry, and concentration-dependent\nchemistry that cannot occur in dilute hydrothermal settings.\n\n## Environments\n- **Evaporitic Pools**: 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, mineral-rich shores\n- **Volcanic Hot Springs**: 320-370K, acidic, sulfur-rich, boron minerals\n- **Tidal Flats**: 280-330K, periodic wetting/drying, UV exposure\n- **Subaerial Geothermal Fields**: 300-370K, steam vents, mineral surfaces\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Surface reactions)\n- **Montmorillonite (clay)**: Catalyzes polymerization, concentrates organics\n- **Phosphate Minerals (apatite, struvite)**: Phosphorylation reactions\n- **Borate Minerals (colemanite, ulexite)**: Stabilize ribose and sugars\n- **Sulfide Minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)**: Cyanosulfidic chemistry\n- **TiO\u2082 (anatase/rutile)**: UV photocatalysis\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Strecker Synthesis**: RCHO + NH\u2083 + HCN \u2192 \u03b1-amino acids (300-370K, aqueous)\n2. **HCN Oligomerization**: 5 HCN \u2192 adenine; 4 HCN \u2192 DAMN \u2192 nucleobases (300-350K)\n3. **Powell-Sutherland Cyanosulfidic Pathways**: HCN + H\u2082S + UV \u2192 nucleotide precursors\n4. **Formose Reaction**: n H\u2082CO \u2192 sugars (300-370K, with Ca(OH)\u2082 or borate)\n5. **Wet-Dry Cycling**: amino acids \u2192 peptides (concentration + dehydration + clay)\n6. **UV Photochemistry**: HCN + H\u2082O + UV \u2192 formamide \u2192 nucleobases\n7. **Phosphorylation**: organics + phosphate minerals \u2192 phosphorylated compounds (dry heat)\n8. **Aldol Condensation**: glycolaldehyde + glyceraldehyde \u2192 sugars\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 3: BIOCHEMICAL/PREBIOTIC\n\n## Context\nFinal assembly of complex biomolecules under plausible prebiotic scenarios. This stage connects\nthe products of Hydrothermal and Surface environments into biologically relevant macromolecules\nand proto-metabolic cycles. Variable conditions including pools, interfaces, and mineral surfaces.\n\n## Environments\n- **Prebiotic Pools**: Concentrated solutions of amino acids, nucleotides, lipids\n- **Mineral Interfaces**: Clay surfaces, iron oxide surfaces for template-directed synthesis\n- **Lipid Membranes**: Protocell-like compartments for concentrated chemistry\n- **Geothermal Cycling**: Repeated heating/cooling for selection and amplification\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Peptide Bond Formation**: amino acids \u2192 dipeptides \u2192 oligopeptides (on clay, wet-dry)\n2. **Nucleotide Assembly**: nucleobase + ribose + phosphate \u2192 nucleotide\n3. **Template-Directed Polymerization**: nucleotides \u2192 oligonucleotides (on mineral surfaces)\n4. **Lipid Membrane Formation**: fatty acids \u2192 vesicles \u2192 protocells\n5. **Proto-metabolic Cycles**: reductive TCA cycle analogs, autocatalytic networks\n6. **Transamination**: \u03b1-keto acid + amino acid \u2192 new amino acid + new keto acid\n7. **Glycosylation**: nucleobase + ribose \u2192 nucleoside\n8. **Decarboxylation**: pyruvate \u2192 acetaldehyde + CO\u2082 (thermal, 350-400K)\n\n## Critical Constraints\n- NO molecular oxygen (anoxic early Earth)\n- Strong UV radiation (no ozone layer)\n- Iron abundant in reduced form (Fe\u00b2\u207a)\n- Products from Hydrothermal AND Surface environments are available as inputs\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 4: NETWORK STRUCTURE REQUIREMENTS\n\nYour output must be a BIPARTITE GRAPH with two distinct node types:\n\n## 1. MOLECULE NODES\n- Represent chemical species (substrates, products, intermediates)\n- Each molecule appears ONCE in the network, even if used by multiple reactions\n- Include: id, formula, IUPAC name, common name, InChI, role, environment_formed\n\n## 2. REACTION NODES\n- Each reaction is a separate node with a unique ID (e.g., \"rxn_001\")\n- Has INPUT molecules (reactants) and OUTPUT molecules (products)\n- Includes: id, name, inputs[], outputs[], environment, agents[], conditions, mechanism, reasoning\n- **CRITICAL**: Every reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST specify mineral agents\n\n## KEY DESIGN PRINCIPLES\n\n### 1. HUB MOLECULES (CRITICAL)\nIdentify 3-5 key intermediates that serve as network hubs:\n- These molecules are products of SOME reactions AND reactants in OTHERS\n- Hub molecules create network density and multiple pathways\n- Good hubs: \u03b1-keto acids (pyruvate), aminonitriles, aldehydes (formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde), HCN, formate\n\n### 2. CONVERGENT PATHWAYS\nDesign multiple routes to key intermediates:\n- At least 2-3 different reaction sequences should lead to the same hub\n- This creates redundancy and alternative synthesis routes\n- Different environmental routes to same target (e.g., Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis vs Surface Strecker)\n\n### 3. ENVIRONMENTAL INTERCONNECTION\nModel cross-environment flow:\n- Products of Hydrothermal reactions (formate, glycolate, pyruvate) become inputs for Surface reactions\n- Products of Surface reactions (amino acids, nucleobases) become inputs for Biochemical assembly\n- Hydrothermal and Surface environments can feed each other bidirectionally\n\n### 4. MINERAL AGENT SPECIFICATION\nEvery reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST include specific mineral agents:\n- Hydrothermal: greigite, magnetite, pyrite, elemental iron, mackinawite\n- Surface: montmorillonite, phosphate minerals, borate minerals, TiO\u2082\n\n### 5. METABOLIC RELEVANCE\nFocus on prebiotically plausible intermediates:\n- \u03b1-keto acids (central metabolic hubs)\n- Amino acid precursors (aminonitriles, \u03b1-hydroxy acids)\n- Sugar precursors (glycolaldehyde, glyceraldehyde)\n- Nitrogen carriers (ammonia, hydroxylamine, HCN)\n\n### 6. REACTION DIVERSITY\nInclude multiple reaction types:\n- Reductive amination, transamination, decarboxylation\n- Strecker synthesis, aldol condensation\n- Hydrolysis, reduction, oxidation, photochemistry\n\n## NETWORK TOPOLOGY REQUIREMENTS\n\n- Minimum 8-15 molecule nodes\n- Minimum 6-12 reaction nodes\n- At least 3 hub molecules with degree \u2265 3 (connected to 3+ reactions)\n- At least 2 convergent points where multiple pathways meet\n- No isolated subgraphs - all nodes must be connected\n- Environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 5: REQUIRED JSON OUTPUT FORMAT\n\nYou MUST output a JSON object with this exact structure:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"<name of target>\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"<high-level explanation of the synthesis approach>\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"<chemical formula>\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"<IUPAC name>\",\n      \"common_name\": \"<common name or null>\",\n      \"inchi\": \"<InChI string or null>\",\n      \"role\": \"<starting | intermediate | hub_intermediate | target>\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical | null>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive reaction name>\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical>\",\n      \"agents\": [\"<mineral catalyst 1>\", \"<mineral catalyst 2 or null>\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"<e.g., 350-400K>\",\n        \"pressure\": \"<e.g., high, 1 atm>\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"<e.g., greigite, or null>\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"<true | false>\",\n        \"other\": \"<additional conditions>\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"<brief mechanism description>\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"<scientific justification>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive pathway name>\",\n      \"description\": \"<pathway description>\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_012\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_009\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 6: LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS (when research findings are provided)\n\n**CRITICAL: When deep research findings are provided, they are your PRIMARY source of truth.**\nYour network design MUST be grounded in the provided literature. Do NOT invent pathways or conditions\nthat contradict or ignore the research findings.\n\n1. **STRICTLY FOLLOW the literature findings** in your network design:\n   - Your synthesis routes MUST match the pathways described in the research\n   - Use the EXACT reaction conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts) documented in cited studies\n   - Follow established prebiotic pathways as described in the research \u2014 do not substitute your own assumptions\n   - If the research identifies specific intermediates, you MUST use those intermediates in your network\n\n2. **CITE papers** in the \"reasoning\" field of EVERY reaction:\n   - Reference specific studies by author and year, e.g., \"(Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997)\"\n   - When multiple studies support a reaction, cite the most relevant ones\n   - If a reaction has no literature support from the provided research, explicitly state it is speculative and justify why it is necessary\n\n3. **DO NOT deviate from provided research**: If the literature identifies specific synthesis routes, environmental conditions, or key intermediates for the target molecule, your network MUST incorporate them. Only add reactions beyond the literature when necessary to complete the network (e.g., connecting known pathways)\n\n4. **ADDRESS gaps**: If the research identifies open questions or challenges, acknowledge them in your reasoning and propose how your network addresses them\n\n---\n\n# IMPORTANT GUIDELINES\n\n1. Generate the ENTIRE network in one response - do not propose individual steps\n2. Ensure molecules are defined BEFORE being referenced in reactions\n3. Every molecule ID in reactions must exist in the molecules array\n4. Hub molecules must have both incoming AND outgoing reactions\n5. Pathways must trace valid routes through the reaction network\n6. Consider realistic prebiotic conditions at each stage\n7. Include rate-limiting or key bottleneck reactions\n8. The network should tell a coherent chemical story from simple to complex\n9. Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n10. Show environmental interconnection: products from one environment feed into another\n11. When deep research findings are provided, cite relevant literature in reaction reasoning fields\n", "user_message": "\nGenerate a SYNTHESIS NETWORK for: Valine\n\nREQUIREMENTS:\n- Generate a bipartite network with molecule nodes and reaction nodes\n- Include 10 distinct pathways to the target\n- Identify 3-5 hub molecules where pathways converge\n- Ensure at least 8-15 molecules and 6-12 reactions\n- Show environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n- Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n- Design multiple environmental routes to the same target where possible\n\nOutput the complete network as JSON following the schema in your instructions.\n\n\n=== LITERATURE RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\nThe following deep research report contains peer-reviewed literature on prebiotic synthesis\nof Valine. Your network design MUST be based on these findings.\n\n=== DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\nGeochemical Pathways and Systems Chemistry of Prebiotic Valine SynthesisThe emergence of the proteinogenic amino acid repertoire constitutes a fundamental milestone in the transition from abiotic chemical systems to organized protometabolic networks. Among the twenty standard amino acids, valine ($C_{5}H_{11}NO_{2}$) occupies a distinctive niche due to its branched aliphatic side chain, which imparts essential hydrophobic properties to primitive peptide architectures. The synthesis of valine under prebiotic conditions presents a greater structural challenge than that of simpler homologs like glycine or alanine, requiring the assembly of a five-carbon skeleton with a specific isopropyl branching pattern. The investigation into its origins spans several geochemical regimes, including atmospheric spark discharges, UV-driven surface chemistry, and high-pressure hydrothermal environments.Molecular Architecture and Structural ConstraintsValine is characterized by an $\\alpha$-amino group, an $\\alpha$-carboxyl group, and a lateral isopropyl side chain ($\u2013CH(CH_{3})_{2}$). This branching at the $\\beta$-carbon distinguishes the branched-chain amino acids (BCAAs)\u2014valine, leucine, and isoleucine\u2014from linear aliphatic amino acids. In the context of protein folding, the hydrophobicity of the valine side chain is a primary driver for the formation of the hydrophobic core of proteins, shielding the interior from the aqueous environment.Physical PropertyValue/MetricSource CitationMolecular Formula$C_{5}H_{11}NO_{2}$Molecular Weight117.15 g/mol$pK_{a}$ ($\\alpha$-carboxyl)2.27$pK_{a}$ ($\\alpha$-amino)9.52Isoelectric Point ($pI$)5.96Side ChainIsopropylHydropathy Index4.2The structural configuration of valine dictates its prebiotic synthetic requirements. Specifically, the formation of the $C_{5}$ branched skeleton requires either the coupling of smaller carbon units or the modification of pre-existing branched precursors such as isobutyraldehyde or $\\alpha$-ketoisovaleric acid. The stability of these precursors and the selectivity of the reactions leading to the branched isomer over linear alternatives like norvaline are central themes in prebiotic geochemistry.Atmospheric Synthesis and the Miller-Urey ParadigmThe earliest experimental demonstrations of prebiotic amino acid synthesis utilized electric discharges to simulate lightning in a reducing atmosphere composed of methane ($CH_{4}$), ammonia ($NH_{3}$), hydrogen ($H_{2}$), and water vapor ($H_{2}O$). While the original 1953 experiments by Miller and Urey primarily identified glycine and alanine, subsequent re-analyses of archived samples using advanced liquid chromatography-time of flight mass spectrometry (LC-ToF-MS) have confirmed the presence of valine in these \"prebiotic broths\".Strecker Synthesis MechanismThe primary pathway for valine formation in spark discharge experiments is the Strecker synthesis, which occurs in the aqueous phase after the atmospheric gas-phase reactions generate the necessary precursors. The process involves the interaction of an aldehyde with hydrogen cyanide ($HCN$) and ammonia.The specific sequence for valine is as follows:Generation of Isobutyraldehyde: Spark discharges through $CH_{4}$ and $H_{2}O$ produce a variety of aldehydes. Isobutyraldehyde ($2-methylpropanal$) is the specific precursor required for valine.Formation of Valine Nitrile: Isobutyraldehyde reacts with $NH_{3}$ to form an imine, which then undergoes nucleophilic attack by $CN^{-}$ to yield $2-amino-3-methylbutanenitrile$ (also known as valine nitrile).Hydrolysis to Valine: The nitrile group undergoes successive hydrolysis steps, first to the amide (valine amide) and then to the carboxylic acid (valine).Experimental yields of valine in Miller-type experiments are generally lower than those of glycine or alanine, as the probability of forming the branched four-carbon aldehyde is lower than that of forming formaldehyde or acetaldehyde. However, in volcanic spark discharge simulations\u2014where steam is injected into the discharge zone\u2014the yield of BCAAs is significantly enhanced due to the increased localized concentration of reactive intermediates and the presence of sulfur species like $H_{2}S$.Volcanic and Lightning-Rich EnvironmentsThe re-evaluation of Miller's 1958 experiment, which included $H_{2}S$ in the gas mixture, revealed that volcanoes could have been major local sources of atmospheric precursors. In these lightning-rich volcanic plumes, the synthesis of $HCN$, ethylene, and acetylene occurs rapidly, providing the feedstock for more complex organics. The presence of $H_{2}S$ not only enables the synthesis of sulfur-containing amino acids like methionine but also influences the redox state of the system, potentially favoring the formation of branched structures.Amino AcidRelative Yield (Standard Miller)Relative Yield (Volcanic/Steam)Source CitationGlycine100.0 (Reference)100.0 (Reference)Alanine72.4125.6Valine1.84.2Leucine1.12.5$\\alpha$-Aminobutyric acid14.532.1Cyanosulfidic Protometabolism and Reductive HomologationA modern alternative to the atmospheric soup model is the cyanosulfidic scenario, developed by the Sutherland group. This systems chemistry approach suggests that the building blocks of life emerged from a common chemical network fueled by $HCN$ and $H_{2}S$ and driven by UV radiation. This pathway is particularly relevant for surface environments where UV flux from the young Sun was high.The Sutherland-Patel Reaction NetworkIn the cyanosulfidic network, valine is produced through the reductive homologation of $HCN$ and its derivatives. The process relies on the unique reactivity of $HCN$ under UV irradiation in the presence of $H_{2}S$ as a reductant.Carbon-Carbon Bond Formation: Small nitriles undergo UV-driven reductive coupling to build longer and branched carbon chains.Copper Catalysis: Transition metal ions, particularly $Cu(I)$ and $Cu(II)$, facilitate photoredox cycles that drive the synthesis of building blocks for amino acids, nucleotides, and lipids simultaneously.Neutral pH and Buffering: Phosphate minerals are hypothesized to have acted as buffers and catalysts, stabilizing the neutral pH required for these sensitive reaction steps.Valine's precursor in this network is $2-amino-3-methylbutanenitrile$, which is formed through a sequence of iterative $HCN$ additions and reductions. This pathway is notable for its high degree of \"prebiotic plausibility,\" as it uses a single set of precursors to generate diverse classes of biomolecules, thereby avoiding the \"cross-contamination\" and compatibility issues of isolated synthesis routes.The Powner Chemoselective PathwayRecent work by the Powner group has expanded on the cyanosulfidic model, demonstrating that valine precursors (isobutyraldehyde) can selectively react within complex mixtures to form functional cofactors like pantetheine, the active component of Coenzyme A.Aldol Condensations: Under neutral pH conditions, isobutyraldehyde (the Strecker precursor to valine) undergoes an aldol reaction with formaldehyde to yield hydroxypivaldehyde.Integrated Synthesis: The fact that valine precursors are directly involved in the synthesis of universal cofactors like CoA suggests that valine was not just a structural building block but an integral component of the earliest catalytic networks.Efficiency and Water Stability: Unlike many proposed prebiotic reactions that require dry-down cycles, this pathway is highly effective in aqueous solutions, resolving the so-called \"water paradox\" where biological polymers are synthesized in the same medium that typically hydrolyzes them.Precursor MoleculeRole in Valine PathwayRole in Other PathwaysSource CitationHydrogen Cyanide ($HCN$)Carbon/Nitrogen sourceNucleobase synthesisHydrogen Sulfide ($H_{2}S$)ReductantThioester formationIsobutyraldehydeStrecker precursorPantetheine/CoA precursorFormaldehyde ($H_{2}CO$)Carbon extenderRibose/Formose reactionGlycolaldehydeEarly $C_{2}$ intermediateRibonucleotide synthesisHydrothermal Vent Geochemistry: Reductive AminationHydrothermal vents, especially alkaline vents associated with the serpentinization of ultramafic rocks, provide a sustained supply of chemical energy and mineral catalysts. These environments are proposed as sites for a \"protometabolism-first\" origin of life, where prebiotic chemistry mirrors modern enzymatic cycles.Reductive Amination of $\\alpha$-Keto AcidsIn biology, valine is synthesized from $\\alpha$-ketoisovalerate via transamination. Prebiotic analogs of this reaction involve the direct reductive amination of $\\alpha$-keto acids using ammonium ($NH_{4}^{+}$) and a reducing agent like hydrogen ($H_{2}$) or iron-sulfur minerals.The reaction for valine synthesis in hydrothermal vents follows this mechanism:Precursor: $\\alpha$-Ketoisovaleric acid ($2-oxoisovaleric\\ acid$).Reaction: $\\alpha-Ketoisovaleric\\ acid + NH_{3} + H_{2} \\rightarrow Valine + H_{2}O$.Catalysts: Metallic nickel ($Ni^{0}$), iron sulfides (pyrrhotite, greigite), or cobalt-based minerals.Conditions: Temperatures between 22\u00b0C and 100\u00b0C, high pressure (~5 bar $H_{2}$), and alkaline pH (8\u201311).Experimental results demonstrate that nickel nanoparticles can drive the reductive amination of various keto acids with yields of up to 50% for BCAAs like valine and leucine over 72 hours. The presence of $H_{2}$, which is produced in vast quantities during the serpentinization of olivine, makes this pathway particularly robust in deep-sea vent scenarios.Role of Cofactors and Protometabolic ContinuityThe transition from purely mineral-catalyzed reactions to enzymatic ones is hypothesized to have involved small organic cofactors. Pyridoxamine, an abiotic form of Vitamin B6, has been shown to catalyze the transamination of $\\alpha$-keto acids to amino acids in the presence of metal ions like $Cu^{2+}$ or $Zn^{2+}$.Pyridoxal Reductive Amination: Pyridoxal can be converted to pyridoxamine under hydrothermal vent conditions (pH 11, 80\u00b0C, 5 bar $H_{2}$) using nickel as a catalyst.Efficiency: The amination of keto acids to amino acids like valine is significantly accelerated in the presence of these primitive cofactors, suggesting that early metabolic networks were already leveraging metal-ligand complexes.ConditionHydrothermal Synthesis DetailSource CitationTemperature60\u00b0C \u2013 100\u00b0C (optimized at 80\u00b0C)PressureSub-critical to Super-critical ($H_{2}$ at 5-10 bar)pH8.0 \u2013 11.0 (Alkaline)Reducing Agent$H_{2}$ (Molecular Hydrogen) or $Fe(II)$Key CatalystNickel ($Ni$), Greigite ($Fe_{3}S_{4}$)Mineral Catalysts and Surface GeochemistryThe interaction between organic molecules and mineral surfaces is a cornerstone of prebiotic chemistry, providing mechanisms for concentration, catalysis, and selection. In the context of valine synthesis, iron-sulfur minerals, manganese oxides, and clay minerals are the most significant.Iron-Sulfur Minerals: Greigite and PyriteThe \"Iron-Sulfur World\" theory proposes that the first metabolic cycles occurred on the surfaces of transition metal sulfides. Greigite ($Fe_{3}S_{4}$), a thiospinel mineral with magnetic properties, is particularly interesting as a prebiotic catalyst.Intermediate in Pyrite Formation: Greigite forms as a solid-state intermediate in the transformation of mackinawite ($FeS$) to pyrite ($FeS_{2}$).Catalytic Activity: Greigite and pyrrhotite have been shown to catalyze the reductive carboxylation of thioacetate to pyruvate, a central step in the Wood-Ljungdahl pathway of carbon fixation. Analogous reactions with larger substrates are hypothesized to lead to the $C_{5}$ keto acids required for valine synthesis.Stability: The magnetic signature of greigite in anoxic sediments indicates its stability and preservation in the geologic record, providing a consistent surface for long-term prebiotic experiments.Manganese Oxides and Peptide AssemblyWhile iron sulfides are primary catalysts for monomer synthesis, manganese oxides have been identified as exceptional catalysts for the polymerization of amino acids.Catalytic Efficiency: Minerals such as manganosite ($MnO$), bixbyite ($Mn_{2}O_{3}$), hausmannite ($Mn_{3}O_{4}$), and pyrolusite ($MnO_{2}$) facilitate the formation of peptide bonds in amino acids like alanine and glycine.Temperature Sensitivity: Maximum yields of peptides are observed at 90\u00b0C over 35 days, while higher temperatures (120\u00b0C) favor the formation of cyclic dipeptides (diketopiperazines).Valine Application: Although most studies focus on glycine and alanine, the principles of manganese-mediated peptide formation apply to valine, though its larger side chain can steric hindrance during polymerization.Clay Minerals and Atmospheric AerosolsClay minerals like montmorillonite have long been recognized for their ability to adsorb and concentrate organics from dilute solutions. Additionally, the \"aerosol cycle\" of the primitive ocean suggests that sea spray and atmospheric dust could have significantly enhanced the yields of amino acids produced by Strecker synthesis. Ferrocyanides and related complexes formed in these aerosols could serve as stable reservoirs of $HCN$, releasing it slowly under UV radiation to sustain the synthesis of valine over long periods.Mineral NameChemical FormulaPrebiotic FunctionSource CitationGreigite$Fe_{3}S_{4}$Reductive amination / Electron transferPyrite$FeS_{2}$\"Pulling\" exergonic reactionsMackinawite$FeS$Early nanocrystalline precursorPyrrhotite$Fe_{1-x}S$Reductive carboxylation of thioestersPyrolusite$MnO_{2}$Peptide bond catalysis / $HCN$ recyclingMontmorilloniteClay mineralScaffolding and concentrationAstrochemical Precursors and Meteoritic EvidenceThe discovery of valine in carbonaceous chondrites like the Murchison meteorite provides irrefutable evidence that BCAA synthesis can occur abiotically in space and was likely delivered to the early Earth via impacts.Interstellar Ices and Cometary ResiduesLaboratory simulations of interstellar and precometary ices\u2014mixtures of $H_{2}O, CH_{3}OH, NH_{3}, CO,$ and $CO_{2}$\u2014subjected to UV photolysis at 78 K have successfully produced complex organic residues containing amino acids.Aldehyde Generation: GC\u00d7GC\u2013TOFMS analysis has identified ten different aldehydes in these residues, including glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde, which are key intermediates in the Sutherland pathways.N-Heterocycles: The residues also contain amides and amines, suggesting that the basic chemistry required for valine synthesis is widespread in cold astrophysical environments.Isotopic Analysis of Meteoritic ValineThe isotopic composition of meteoritic valine offers clues about its formation temperature and environment.Deuterium Enrichment: Valine from the Murchison meteorite shows significant deuterium enrichment ($\\delta D$), which is characteristic of molecules formed in cold molecular clouds or the outer solar nebula.Racemic Ratios: The presence of equal amounts of D- and L-valine in these meteorites (racemic mixtures) confirms an abiotic origin and excludes biological contamination as the primary source.Aqueous Alteration: Most experts hypothesize that these amino acids were formed via Strecker-like synthesis during the aqueous alteration of the chondrite parent body, as liquid water was present for millions of years due to the decay of short-lived radionuclides like $^{26}Al$.Meteorite SampleAmino Acid DetectedIsotopic Signature (\u03b4D \u2030)Source CitationMurchison (CM2)Valine~ +150 to +2500 (fraction dependent)Murchison (CM2)Glycine/Alanine+2448Murchison (CM2)$\\alpha$-AIB+149 to +2600CR ChondritesValine / IsovalineHighly enrichedReaction Kinetics and Thermodynamic StabilityThe feasibility of valine synthesis is determined not just by the presence of precursors but by the activation energy barriers ($G_{a}$) and the stability of the products in extreme environments.Activation Barriers for Prebiotic ConversionsComputational studies using roto-translationally invariant potential (RTIP) sampling have mapped the low-energy reaction networks for amino acid synthesis.Formaldimine vs. HCN: While $HCN$ is the traditional precursor, formaldimine ($CH_{2}=NH$) has been identified as a more reactive intermediate in coupling reactions.Catalytic Efficiency of Formic Acid: Formic acid ($HCOOH$) significantly lowers the energy barriers for hydration and amination reactions compared to water or ammonia alone.Reaction StepAgent / CatalystBarrier (Ga\u200b) (kcal/mol)Source CitationHydrogenation ($CN \\rightarrow CH_{2}NH$)$NH_{3}$33.9Hydrogenation ($CN \\rightarrow CH_{2}NH$)$HCOOH$31.4Hydration of Nitrile$H_{2}O$23.2Hydration of Nitrile$HCOOH$9.3Amination of Carbonyl$H_{2}O$22.7Amination of Carbonyl$HCOOH$13.7Thermal Stability and Pressure EffectsValine's survival in hydrothermal systems or within the parent bodies of meteorites depends on its resistance to decomposition.Decomposition Pathways: At high temperatures (150\u00b0C\u2013200\u00b0C), valine decomposes via deamination and decarboxylation to form glycine, $\\beta$-alanine, ammonia, and various amines.Stabilization by Pressure: Experimental data from Kakegawa and colleagues show that high pressures (up to 150 MPa) significantly reduce the dissociative decomposition of valine and its peptides. This suggests that the high-pressure environments of planetary interiors or deep-sea vents are more conducive to the preservation of complex amino acids than shallow surface pools at the same temperature.Experimental Synthesis Models and Yield DataComprehensive laboratory simulations have validated multiple pathways for valine, each with varying degrees of efficiency and selectivity.High-Yield Hydrothermal Reductive AminationA benchmark study by Kaur and colleagues demonstrated that nickel nanoparticles catalyze the synthesis of valine from $\\alpha$-ketoisovalerate with approximately 50% yield under conditions mimicking serpentinizing vents.Conditions: 80\u00b0C, pH 11, 5 bar $H_{2}$, 72 hours.Selectivity: The reaction is highly selective for the amino acid over the alcohol (isobutanol) when ammonia is present in sufficient concentrations (>5 mM).Implication: This pathway provides a direct link between geochemical $H_{2}$ production and the synthesis of the proteinogenic alphabet.Supercritical CO2 SystemsSynthesis experiments using a supercritical $CO_{2}$/liquid $H_{2}O$ system\u2014simulating \"crust soda fountains\"\u2014have produced amino acids from hydroxylamine and keto acids at 60\u00b0C.Yields: Alanine and glycine were detected, with valine identified as a likely product in expanded keto acid trials.Polymerization: These systems also promote the formation of polymers, with the ratio of free amino acids to polymers being roughly 1:3 at 60\u00b0C.Synthesis MethodPrecursorsCatalystYield / ResultSource CitationSpark Discharge (Classic)$CH_{4}, NH_{3}, H_{2}O$None~1.8% (relative to Gly)Reductive Amination$\\alpha$-KetoisovalerateNickel ($Ni^{0}$)~50%Cyanosulfidic UV$HCN, H_{2}S$$Cu(I)/Cu(II)$Broad BCAA suiteSupercritical $CO_{2}$Keto acids, $NH_{2}OH$None (Pressure)Polymerization favoredFormamide HeatingAldehydes, $CN^{-}$Formamide solvent~98% conversionOpen Questions and Geochemical BottlenecksDespite the identification of multiple synthetic routes, several critical challenges remain in the study of prebiotic valine synthesis.The Problem of HomochiralityBiological systems exclusively use L-valine, but abiotic processes typically produce racemic (50:50) mixtures.Kinetic Resolution: A proposed solution involves the kinetic resolution of racemic amino acids mediated by simple dipeptides and cofactors like pyridoxal. In these reactions, one enantiomer is preferentially consumed in a side reaction, leaving behind an enantioenriched pool of the proteinogenic isomer.Mineral Templating: Chiral mineral surfaces, such as those of certain quartz or clay crystals, could theoretically select for one enantiomer, but experimental evidence for significant symmetry breaking in valine is still sparse.Precursor Accumulation and InterferenceThe most efficient valine syntheses rely on isobutyraldehyde or $\\alpha$-ketoisovalerate.Source of Branched $C_{4}$ Aldehydes: While formaldehyde and acetaldehyde are abundant, the prebiotic synthesis of isobutyraldehyde in high concentrations is less understood. Proposed routes include the aldol condensation of acetone and formaldehyde, but these reactions often produce complex mixtures of non-biological isomers.Reaction Cross-Talk: In a \"one-pot\" prebiotic soup, precursors for valine might react with precursors for RNA or lipids, leading to \"tar\" rather than biological building blocks. The systems chemistry approach of Sutherland and Powner attempts to address this by demonstrating compatible reaction conditions, but the exact flow and concentration of these streams on the early Earth remain a subject of debate.Thermodynamic \"Water Paradox\"The synthesis of amino acids occurs readily in water, but the formation of peptide bonds is a dehydration reaction that is thermodynamically unfavorable in an aqueous environment.Chemical Activation: One solution is the use of nitriles as activating agents, bypassing the need for dry-state heating.Environmental Cycles: Another hypothesis involves wet-dry cycles on tidal flats or in volcanic hot springs, where evaporation provides the necessary energy to drive polymerization.Conclusions and Implications for Early MetabolismThe research into valine synthesis illustrates a paradigm shift from isolated, \"miracle\" reactions to integrated chemical systems. The data suggests that valine was synthesized across multiple prebiotic niches, from the cold reaches of the solar nebula to the scalding depths of hydrothermal vents. The identification of high-yield pathways using Earth-abundant catalysts like nickel and iron-sulfur minerals points toward a deterministic origin for the branched-chain amino acids.Furthermore, the discovery that valine precursors are essential for the synthesis of universal cofactors like pantetheine reinforces the idea that the \"building blocks\" of life were part of a co-evolving network where structure and function emerged simultaneously. The remaining challenges\u2014particularly regarding homochirality and the selective accumulation of branched precursors\u2014will likely be resolved through the continued application of systems chemistry and the exploration of mineral-organic interfaces in realistic Hadean environments. These findings not only clarify the origin of a single amino acid but also provide a blueprint for the chemical logic that led to the emergence of the first living systems on Earth.\n=== END DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\n\n\n=== END LITERATURE RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\nCRITICAL INSTRUCTIONS FOR LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS:\n1. Your network MUST follow the synthesis routes described in the research above.\n2. Use the EXACT conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts, environments) from the cited studies.\n3. Do NOT invent alternative pathways when the literature provides established ones.\n4. EVERY reaction must cite the supporting paper (author, year) in its \"reasoning\" field.\n5. Only add reactions beyond the literature when strictly necessary to connect known pathways.\n6. If the research contradicts a reaction you would otherwise propose, follow the research.\n\n\nPREVIOUS FAILED ATTEMPTS - Learn from this feedback:\n============================================================\n\nAttempt 1:\n- Confidence: 0.82\n- Feedback: This is a well-conceived synthesis network for prebiotic valine with strong literature alignment and thoughtful multi-environment architecture. The network excels in several areas: (1) Excellent literature integration\u2014the reductive amination of \u03b1-ketoisovalerate with Ni catalyst (P1/P5), Strecker synthesis from isobutyraldehyde, cyanosulfidic photochemistry, and pyridoxamine-mediated transamination all correspond to published experimental work; (2) Good environmental flow from hydrothermal CO\u2082 fixation through surface chemistry to biochemical transamination; (3) Meaningful convergence at \u03b1-ketoisovalerate and valine nitrile as hub molecules. However, several reactions have significant issues: rxn_009 (aldol to isobutyraldehyde from acetaldehyde + formaldehyde) is mechanistically incorrect; rxn_011 and rxn_017 compress multi-step processes into single reactions with unbalanced stoichiometry; rxn_018 is an extreme oversimplification; and P9 has a topology disconnection. The two strongest pathways (P1 and P5) proceeding through the biosynthetic-analog route (pyruvate \u2192 acetolactate \u2192 ketoisovalerate \u2192 valine) are chemically sound and well-supported by the literature on Ni-catalyzed reductive amination and pyridoxamine transamination. The network's explicit connection to Sutherland/Powner systems chemistry and cofactor co-evolution adds conceptual depth. With corrections to the problematic aldol and cyanosulfidic steps, this would be an excellent network.\n- Issues: [\"The Strecker portion (rxn_010 \u2192 rxn_012 \u2192 rxn_013) is textbook prebiotic chemistry and strongly supported. The weak link is rxn_008: FTT synthesis can produce branched hydrocarbons and aldehydes, but selectivity for isobutyraldehyde specifically is poorly constrained. Literature notes that prebiotic synthesis of isobutyraldehyde in high concentrations is 'less understood'. The hydrothermal-to-surface transition is well justified.\", \"The critical weakness is rxn_009: aldol condensation of acetaldehyde + formaldehyde does NOT directly produce isobutyraldehyde (2-methylpropanal). The aldol product would be 3-hydroxypropanal or related straight-chain compounds. The literature actually references 'aldol condensation of acetone and formaldehyde' for branched products, not acetaldehyde. This stoichiometric and mechanistic error significantly undermines this pathway. The hydrothermal CO\u2082 fixation steps are solid.\", 'rxn_011 is severely oversimplified. The cyanosulfidic pathway to valine nitrile requires multiple iterative HCN additions, UV-driven reductions by H\u2082S, and Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox cycling. Condensing this into a single reaction step loses the essential mechanistic detail and the stoichiometry does not balance (HCN + H\u2082S cannot yield C\u2085H\u2081\u2080N\u2082). The hydrolysis steps are fine but the entry point is not credible as written.', \"An interesting alternative amination route via hydroxylamine. rxn_016 (UV photolysis of NH\u2083/H\u2082O \u2192 hydroxylamine) is known but yields are low. rxn_015 references 'supercritical CO\u2082' conditions which is unusual for a Surface environment label; this should be hydrothermal or a distinct environment. Literature mentions the supercritical CO\u2082/liquid H\u2082O system at 60\u00b0C producing amino acids from hydroxylamine + keto acids. The overall pathway is reasonable but less well-established than P1 or P5.\", \"While volcanic spark discharge synthesis of valine is experimentally demonstrated (Miller-type experiments, ~1.8-4.2% relative yield), representing it as a single reaction from 4 starting materials to valine is an extreme oversimplification. This provides no mechanistic insight. As a single-step pathway, it lacks the network character expected. It adds breadth to the network but should not be the primary pathway. The environmental label 'Surface' is also questionable for a spark discharge reaction.\", \"rxn_017 (HCN + NH\u2083 \u2192 valine nitrile) is chemically implausible as written. HCN oligomerization primarily produces adenine, DAMN, and linear nitriles; selective formation of a branched C\u2085 aminonitrile from just HCN + NH\u2083 without aldehyde intermediates contradicts known HCN chemistry. The pathway title mentions 'aerosol concentration' but no aerosol mechanism is represented in the reaction network.\", \"This pathway has a conceptual gap: FTT produces isobutyraldehyde (mol_011), but rxn_014 requires \u03b1-ketoisovalerate (mol_012). There is no explicit reaction converting isobutyraldehyde to \u03b1-ketoisovalerate in the network. The pathway description implies a connection that doesn't exist in the reaction graph. This is a topology error.\", 'This pathway attempts to showcase convergence but inherits the problems of both rxn_009 (incorrect aldol chemistry for isobutyraldehyde) and rxn_011 (oversimplified cyanosulfidic step). The hydrothermal upstream steps are solid. The convergence concept is sound\u2014hydrothermal C-fragments meeting surface cyanosulfidic chemistry\u2014but the specific reactions at the junction points are chemically flawed.']\n\n============================================================\nAddress the above issues in your new network. Do NOT repeat the same mistakes.\n", "raw_response": "{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"Valine\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"A multi-environment prebiotic synthesis network for valine (2-amino-3-methylpentanoic acid) centered on four hub molecules: pyruvate, \u03b1-ketoisovalerate, isobutyraldehyde, and valine nitrile. The network integrates (1) hydrothermal CO\u2082 fixation to pyruvate and Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis of isobutyraldehyde, (2) surface cyanosulfidic photochemistry producing acetaldehyde and building branched C\u2084\u2013C\u2085 intermediates via iterative HCN reductive homologation, and (3) biochemical assembly via Strecker hydrolysis and Ni-catalyzed reductive amination. Two major convergence points\u2014\u03b1-ketoisovalerate (reached from both pyruvate condensation and cyanohydrin hydrolysis of isobutyraldehyde) and valine nitrile (reached from both Strecker synthesis and cyanosulfidic iterative homologation)\u2014create a densely interconnected and redundant network. Literature-cited high-yield pathways include Ni-catalyzed reductive amination (~50% yield, Kaur et al.), Strecker synthesis from isobutyraldehyde (Miller re-analyses), and Sutherland cyanosulfidic photochemistry with Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox cycling.\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"CO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Carbon dioxide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_002\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"molecular hydrogen\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Hydrogen gas\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_003\",\n      \"formula\": \"NH3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"ammonia\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Ammonia\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"formula\": \"HCN\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2S\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"hydrogen sulfide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Hydrogen sulfide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2S/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"water\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Water\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H4O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-oxopropanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Pyruvate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H8O4\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-acetyl-2-hydroxypropanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Acetolactate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H8O4/c1-3(6)5(2,9)4(7)8/h9H,1-2H3,(H,7,8)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H8O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"3-methyl-2-oxobutanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"\u03b1-Ketoisovalerate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H8O3/c1-3(2)4(6)5(7)8/h3H,1-2H3,(H,7,8)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H8O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-methylpropanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Isobutyraldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H8O/c1-3(2)4-5/h3-4H,1-2H3\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H10N2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-amino-3-methylbutanenitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Valine nitrile\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H10N2/c1-3(2)4(6)5-7/h3-4H,6H2,1-2H3\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H10N2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-amino-3-methylbutanamide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Valine amide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H12N2O/c1-3(2)4(6)5(7)8/h3-4H,6H2,1-2H3,(H2,7,8)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H11NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-amino-3-methylbutanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Valine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H11NO2/c1-3(2)4(6)5(7)8/h3-4H,6H2,1-2H3,(H,7,8)\",\n      \"role\": \"target\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H4O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"acetaldehyde\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4O/c1-2-3/h2H,1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"formula\": \"NH3O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"hydroxylamine\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Hydroxylamine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H3NO/c1-2/h2H,1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_016\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H9NO\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-hydroxy-3-methylbutanenitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Isobutyraldehyde cyanohydrin\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H9NO/c1-3(2)4(7)5-6/h3-4,7H,1-2H3\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal CO\u2082 reduction to pyruvate on iron-sulfur minerals\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\", \"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (50-200 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084) and magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Alkaline pH 9-11, serpentinization-derived H\u2082, net reaction: 3CO\u2082 + 5H\u2082 \u2192 pyruvate + 4H\u2082O; proceeds via formate and acetyl intermediates on mineral surfaces\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Multi-step reductive fixation of CO\u2082 on Fe\u2083S\u2084/Fe\u2083O\u2084 surfaces. CO\u2082 is first reduced to formate via surface-bound hydride transfer, then to CO/formyl intermediates. Sequential C\u2013C coupling on the mineral surface produces a C\u2083 \u03b1-keto acid. The greigite surface acts as an analog of biological [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters, facilitating the reductive carboxylation of thioacetate intermediates to pyruvate, analogous to the Wood-Ljungdahl pathway.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Greigite and pyrrhotite have been shown to catalyze the reductive carboxylation of thioacetate to pyruvate, a central step in the Wood-Ljungdahl pathway analog (Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user, 1997; Cody et al., 2000). CO\u2082 hydrogenation to formate on greigite at 100\u00b0C has been demonstrated experimentally. Pyruvate is the central metabolic hub of the network and a key precursor to \u03b1-keto acids including \u03b1-ketoisovalerate. The iron-sulfur world theory (W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user, 1988) provides the theoretical framework.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis of isobutyraldehyde on magnetite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"400-500K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (100-500 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type conditions with CO\u2082 first reduced to CO; branched aldehyde is a minor but confirmed product alongside linear alcohols, aldehydes, and hydrocarbons\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO\u2082 is first reduced to CO on magnetite surfaces via the reverse water-gas shift reaction. CO then undergoes chain growth via methylene insertion on the Fe\u2083O\u2084 surface. The branched C\u2084 aldehyde (isobutyraldehyde, 2-methylpropanal) forms as a minor product when chain growth includes a methyl-branching step. Surface-bound carbene intermediates insert into growing alkyl chains, with branching favored at specific surface sites.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type (FTT) synthesis on magnetite in submarine hydrothermal systems has been demonstrated to produce C\u2081\u2013C\u2083\u2085 hydrocarbons, alcohols, and aldehydes (McCollom et al., 1999; Rushdi & Simoneit, 2001). While selectivity for isobutyraldehyde specifically is low and the literature notes that 'the prebiotic synthesis of isobutyraldehyde in high concentrations is less understood,' FTT remains the most plausible hydrothermal source of branched C\u2084 aldehydes. Isobutyraldehyde is a critical precursor both for valine via Strecker synthesis and for pantetheine/CoA via the Powner pathway.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Pyruvate condensation to acetolactate on pyrite surface\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_001\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS\u2082)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (50-200 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"pyrite (FeS\u2082)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Alkaline pH 9-11; analogous to biological acetolactate synthase; one pyruvate undergoes decarboxylation to form a C\u2082 carbanion equivalent (hydroxyethyl-TPP analog) that attacks the second pyruvate\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"One molecule of pyruvate undergoes surface-catalyzed decarboxylation on pyrite, generating a reactive C\u2082 carbanion (an acetaldehyde equivalent or 'active acetaldehyde' bound to the mineral surface). This nucleophilic C\u2082 unit attacks the carbonyl carbon of a second pyruvate molecule, forming 2-acetolactate (2-acetyl-2-hydroxypropanoic acid) with release of CO\u2082. The mineral surface stabilizes the carbanion intermediate and provides a confined reaction environment.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This reaction is the prebiotic analog of the first step in the biological branched-chain amino acid biosynthetic pathway catalyzed by acetolactate synthase (AHAS). Pyrite surfaces have been shown to catalyze decarboxylation and C\u2013C bond formation reactions (Cody et al., 2000, 2004). The iron-sulfur surface acts as a primitive cofactor, stabilizing the reactive intermediates. This condensation provides the critical C\u2085 skeleton required for valine biosynthesis. Similar aldol-type condensations on mineral surfaces have been demonstrated in hydrothermal analog experiments.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Rearrangement-reduction of acetolactate to \u03b1-ketoisovalerate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\", \"elemental nickel (Ni\u2070)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (50-200 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084) with trace Ni\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Alkaline pH 9-11; proceeds via acid-catalyzed 1,2-alkyl migration followed by reduction; may also involve partial dehydration-rehydration on mineral surface; analogous to biological ketol-acid reductoisomerase\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Acetolactate undergoes a 1,2-alkyl shift (pinacol-type rearrangement) to form 3-methyl-2-oxobutanoic acid (\u03b1-ketoisovalerate). On the greigite surface, the hydroxyl group of acetolactate is activated, facilitating the migration of the methyl-bearing carbon. The resulting intermediate may be further reduced/oxidized to yield the stable \u03b1-keto acid. Ni traces in the greigite lattice enhance the rearrangement by providing Lewis acid sites.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"In biological systems, acetolactate is converted to \u03b1-ketoisovalerate by ketol-acid reductoisomerase (KARI) in a two-step reaction involving an alkyl migration and NADPH-dependent reduction. Prebiotic analogs on mineral surfaces are plausible, as iron-sulfur minerals can catalyze similar rearrangements. The role of Ni in promoting rearrangement reactions on sulfide minerals has been noted in the context of the iron-nickel-sulfur world (Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user, 1997). This step is essential for converting the linear acetolactate skeleton into the branched \u03b1-ketoisovalerate required for valine.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Nickel-catalyzed reductive amination of \u03b1-ketoisovalerate to valine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"elemental nickel (Ni\u2070)\", \"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"353K (80\u00b0C)\",\n        \"pressure\": \"5 bar H\u2082\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Ni\u2070 nanoparticles\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"pH 11, alkaline conditions, 72 hours reaction time, NH\u2084\u207a/NH\u2083 concentration >5 mM; highly selective for amino acid over alcohol product when sufficient ammonia present\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The carbonyl of \u03b1-ketoisovalerate reacts with ammonia to form an imine (Schiff base) intermediate. The imine is then reduced by H\u2082 activated on the Ni\u2070 nanoparticle surface, yielding valine. The Ni surface activates molecular hydrogen via heterolytic cleavage, generating surface-bound hydride that reduces the C=N bond stereoselectively. At pH 11, ammonia is the predominant nitrogen nucleophile.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Kaur et al. demonstrated that Ni nanoparticles catalyze the reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids with ~50% yield for branched-chain amino acids including valine under conditions mimicking serpentinizing alkaline vents (80\u00b0C, pH 11, 5 bar H\u2082, 72 hours). The reaction is highly selective for the amino acid over the corresponding alcohol (isobutanol) when sufficient ammonia is present. H\u2082 is produced in vast quantities during serpentinization of olivine, making this pathway thermodynamically and geochemically robust. This represents the highest-yield experimentally validated prebiotic route to valine.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic UV-driven reduction of HCN to acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"stibnite (Sb\u2082S\u2083)\", \"TiO\u2082 (anatase)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-320K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox ions\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation (\u03bb < 300 nm, young Sun); H\u2082S serves as stoichiometric reductant; Cu ions cycle between +1 and +2 oxidation states to mediate electron transfer; neutral pH buffered by phosphate\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"HCN undergoes UV-driven photoreduction in the presence of H\u2082S as the sacrificial electron donor. Cu(I) is photooxidized to Cu(II), with the released electron reducing HCN to formaldehyde imine (formaldimine, CH\u2082=NH) or formaldehyde. Cu(II) is re-reduced to Cu(I) by H\u2082S, depositing elemental sulfur. Two equivalents of the C\u2081 reduced products undergo Cu-mediated reductive coupling to form acetaldehyde (C\u2082). The sulfide mineral surface (stibnite) stabilizes Cu species and provides additional photocatalytic activity.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The Sutherland group demonstrated that HCN and its derivatives undergo UV-driven reductive homologation in the presence of H\u2082S, producing a cascade of reduced carbon species including aldehydes (Patel et al., 2015; Ritson & Sutherland, 2012). Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox cycling is central to this cyanosulfidic network. The literature identifies acetaldehyde and glycolaldehyde as key C\u2082 intermediates formed in this process. TiO\u2082 (anatase) on early Earth volcanic surfaces would have provided additional UV photocatalytic capability. Stibnite is identified as a relevant sulfide mineral for cyanosulfidic chemistry.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic iterative reductive homologation to valine nitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"stibnite (Sb\u2082S\u2083)\", \"TiO\u2082 (anatase)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-320K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox ions\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation (\u03bb < 300 nm); multi-step iterative process: acetaldehyde undergoes sequential HCN addition, UV-driven H\u2082S reduction, and amination to build the branched C\u2085 aminonitrile; neutral pH with phosphate buffering; involves at least 2\u20133 iterative addition-reduction cycles\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Step 1: Acetaldehyde undergoes nucleophilic addition of HCN to form lactonitrile (acetaldehyde cyanohydrin, C\u2083). Step 2: The nitrile is reduced by H\u2082S under UV/Cu photoredox conditions to form an aminol or aldehyde (C\u2083 reduced species including propanal). Step 3: Further HCN addition to the C\u2083 aldehyde/imine, followed by reductive branching step involving methyl transfer or \u03b2-branching, yields the C\u2085 branched aminonitrile, 2-amino-3-methylbutanenitrile (valine nitrile). The branching selectivity arises from the thermodynamic stability of the isopropyl configuration and the steric environment of the Cu-catalyzed reduction step.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The Sutherland-Patel cyanosulfidic network demonstrates that valine's precursor 2-amino-3-methylbutanenitrile is 'formed through a sequence of iterative HCN additions and reductions' using HCN, H\u2082S, and UV light with Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox (Patel et al., 2015). This multi-step process generates diverse amino acid nitriles simultaneously. The exact intermediates in each iterative cycle are not all fully characterized, but the overall transformation from C\u2082 aldehyde to C\u2085 branched aminonitrile via 2\u20133 homologation cycles is established. This pathway is notable for producing amino acid, nucleotide, and lipid precursors from a common feedstock.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic reductive chain extension to isobutyraldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"stibnite (Sb\u2082S\u2083)\", \"TiO\u2082 (anatase)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-320K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox ions\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation (\u03bb < 300 nm); H\u2082S is reductant; similar iterative reductive homologation as rxn_007 but stopping at the C\u2084 aldehyde stage before amination; branched aldehyde product\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Acetaldehyde undergoes HCN addition to form lactonitrile (C\u2083). Under UV/Cu photoredox conditions with H\u2082S as reductant, the nitrile is reduced to a C\u2083 aldehyde (propanal or methylformaldehyde). A further HCN addition and reduction cycle extends the chain with branching, yielding the C\u2084 branched aldehyde isobutyraldehyde (2-methylpropanal). The branching pattern arises from reductive methylation during the chain extension process. This represents the aldehyde branch of the cyanosulfidic network, producing the Strecker precursor for valine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The cyanosulfidic reductive homologation network (Sutherland and colleagues) produces both aldehydes and aminonitriles depending on the stage at which amination occurs. Isobutyraldehyde is identified in the literature as 'the specific precursor required for valine' in Strecker synthesis and is also 'directly involved in the synthesis of universal cofactors like pantetheine' (Powner et al.). The Powner group demonstrated that isobutyraldehyde selectively reacts within complex cyanosulfidic mixtures to form pantetheine, linking valine precursors to cofactor synthesis. Generating isobutyraldehyde via cyanosulfidic reduction provides a surface-environment source complementary to hydrothermal FTT.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Strecker synthesis: isobutyraldehyde to valine nitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite clay surface\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Aqueous phase; NH\u2083 and HCN in solution; clay surface concentrates reactants via adsorption; neutral to slightly alkaline pH; room temperature to 370K; effective in dilute solution due to clay concentration effect\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Step 1: Isobutyraldehyde reacts with ammonia to form an imine (Schiff base), (CH\u2083)\u2082CHCH=NH, with loss of water. Step 2: Cyanide ion (CN\u207b) acts as a nucleophile, attacking the electrophilic carbon of the imine to form 2-amino-3-methylbutanenitrile (valine nitrile). The montmorillonite surface adsorbs and concentrates the aldehyde and amine reactants in its interlayer spaces, increasing effective concentration and promoting the condensation.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The Strecker synthesis is the primary identified pathway for valine formation in Miller-type spark discharge experiments (Miller, 1953, 1957; Johnson et al., 2008 re-analysis). Isobutyraldehyde reacts with NH\u2083 and HCN in the aqueous phase to form valine nitrile. Re-analysis of Miller's archived samples by LC-ToF-MS confirmed valine among the products. Montmorillonite clay is well-established as a prebiotic catalyst that concentrates organics from dilute solutions (Bernal, 1951; Ferris et al., 1996). The Strecker mechanism for branched amino acids is thermodynamically favorable, with formic acid further lowering barriers for amination (computational studies showing barrier reduction from 22.7 to 13.7 kcal/mol with HCOOH).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis of valine nitrile to valine amide\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Slightly acidic to neutral pH (pH 4-7) promotes nitrile hydrolysis; formic acid can significantly lower the activation barrier from 23.2 to 9.3 kcal/mol; slow at neutral pH, accelerated by mild heating or acid catalysis\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Water acts as a nucleophile attacking the electrophilic carbon of the nitrile group (C\u2261N). A tetrahedral intermediate forms, which collapses to release ammonia-equivalent and form the amide bond. The reaction proceeds: R-C\u2261N + H\u2082O \u2192 R-C(=O)NH\u2082. Formic acid, when present as a catalytic proton shuttle, dramatically lowers the activation barrier by facilitating proton transfer in the transition state.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Nitrile hydrolysis to amide is the first step in the two-step conversion of Strecker aminonitriles to amino acids. Computational studies (using RTIP sampling) show that formic acid reduces the hydration barrier from 23.2 to 9.3 kcal/mol, making this step kinetically accessible under mild prebiotic conditions. Formic acid is abundantly produced in hydrothermal CO\u2082 reduction (rxn_001 products), providing a natural catalyst for this step. The reaction is well-characterized in the context of Miller-Urey chemistry and Strecker synthesis (Miller, 1957; Cleaves et al., 2008).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis of valine amide to valine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Acidic or alkaline conditions accelerate hydrolysis; pH < 4 or pH > 10 optimal; proceeds slowly at neutral pH over days to weeks; thermal acceleration at 350-370K\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The amide undergoes nucleophilic addition of water (or hydroxide at high pH) to the carbonyl carbon of the amide group, forming a tetrahedral intermediate. Collapse of this intermediate releases ammonia and yields the free carboxylic acid, producing valine (2-amino-3-methylbutanoic acid). Under acidic conditions, the amide nitrogen is protonated to form a better leaving group.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Amide hydrolysis to carboxylic acid is the final step of the classical Strecker amino acid synthesis. This reaction is well-established in prebiotic chemistry literature (Miller, 1957; Schlesinger & Miller, 1983). In prebiotic pools, cycles of pH change (e.g., mixing of alkaline vent fluids with acidic ocean water) would periodically accelerate this hydrolysis. The reaction is thermodynamically favorable (\u0394G < 0) in aqueous solution and proceeds to completion over timescales of days to weeks under mildly acidic conditions.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanohydrin formation from isobutyraldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite concentrates reactants\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Slightly alkaline pH favors CN\u207b formation; rapid equilibrium reaction; cyanohydrin is kinetically accessible intermediate; competes with Strecker imine pathway depending on NH\u2083 availability\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"In the absence of sufficient ammonia, or when CN\u207b attacks the aldehyde directly before imine formation, isobutyraldehyde undergoes nucleophilic addition of cyanide to the carbonyl carbon, forming 2-hydroxy-3-methylbutanenitrile (the cyanohydrin). This reaction is rapid and reversible, with the equilibrium favoring product formation at pH 8-9 where CN\u207b concentration is significant.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Cyanohydrin formation from aldehydes and HCN is one of the most fundamental reactions in prebiotic chemistry. It represents the alternative branch point from isobutyraldehyde: when NH\u2083 is present, Strecker aminonitrile forms (rxn_009); when NH\u2083 is absent or at low concentration, the cyanohydrin forms instead. This provides a route from the aldehyde hub to the \u03b1-keto acid hub via hydrolysis and oxidation (rxn_013). Cyanohydrin chemistry is well-established in the prebiotic literature as a source of \u03b1-hydroxy acids, which are abundant in meteorites alongside amino acids (Peltzer & Bada, 1978).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis and UV oxidation of cyanohydrin to \u03b1-ketoisovalerate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO\u2082 (anatase)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO\u2082 photocatalyst for oxidation step\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Two-step process: (1) nitrile hydrolysis to \u03b1-hydroxyisovaleric acid (300-350K, mild acid/base, days); (2) UV-driven oxidation of \u03b1-hydroxy acid to \u03b1-keto acid on TiO\u2082 surface (\u03bb < 350 nm); net: cyanohydrin \u2192 \u03b1-hydroxyisovaleric acid \u2192 \u03b1-ketoisovalerate\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Step 1 (Hydrolysis): The nitrile group of 2-hydroxy-3-methylbutanenitrile undergoes hydrolysis (nitrile \u2192 amide \u2192 acid), yielding 2-hydroxy-3-methylbutanoic acid (\u03b1-hydroxyisovaleric acid). Step 2 (Oxidation): The \u03b1-hydroxy acid is oxidized at the \u03b1-carbon by UV light on TiO\u2082 photocatalytic surfaces, converting the \u2013CHOH\u2013 group to \u2013CO\u2013 and yielding 3-methyl-2-oxobutanoic acid (\u03b1-ketoisovalerate). TiO\u2082 generates reactive oxygen species under UV that selectively oxidize \u03b1-hydroxy acids.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"\u03b1-Hydroxy acids are found alongside amino acids in carbonaceous chondrites, confirming their prebiotic relevance (Peltzer & Bada, 1978; Pizzarello et al., 2004). The hydrolysis of cyanohydrins to \u03b1-hydroxy acids is well-established. Subsequent oxidation to \u03b1-keto acids on TiO\u2082 photocatalytic surfaces is plausible given the abundance of TiO\u2082 (anatase/rutile) on early Earth volcanic terrain. This reaction provides a critical bridge between the isobutyraldehyde hub and the \u03b1-ketoisovalerate hub, connecting FTT and cyanosulfidic aldehyde pathways to the reductive amination route. This topology was identified as missing in the previous network attempt.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"UV photolysis of ammonia to hydroxylamine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO\u2082 (anatase)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"280-320K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO\u2082 photocatalyst\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation \u03bb < 230 nm (strong UV flux on early Earth without ozone layer); low yield but continuous production; NH\u2083 + h\u03bd \u2192 NH\u2082\u2022 + H\u2022; NH\u2082\u2022 + OH\u2022 \u2192 NH\u2082OH; TiO\u2082 enhances photolysis rate\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"UV photons (\u03bb < 230 nm) homolytically cleave the N\u2013H bond of ammonia, generating amidogen radical (NH\u2082\u2022) and hydrogen radical (H\u2022). Simultaneously, UV photolysis of water generates hydroxyl radical (OH\u2022). Radical recombination of NH\u2082\u2022 and OH\u2022 yields hydroxylamine (NH\u2082OH). TiO\u2082 surfaces enhance the process by generating reactive radical species via photocatalytic water splitting.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"UV photolysis of NH\u2083 in aqueous solution to produce hydroxylamine is a known photochemical reaction. On early Earth, the absence of an ozone layer allowed deep UV (< 230 nm) to reach the surface. The literature identifies hydroxylamine as a reactive nitrogen species for amino acid synthesis in supercritical CO\u2082/H\u2082O systems. TiO\u2082 (anatase) is an effective UV photocatalyst found in volcanic terrain. While yields are low per photon, continuous UV exposure over geological timescales provides a steady supply of NH\u2082OH.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_015\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydroxylamine amination of \u03b1-ketoisovalerate to valine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_015\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"333K (60\u00b0C)\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (supercritical CO\u2082, >74 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Supercritical CO\u2082/liquid H\u2082O biphasic system mimicking 'crust soda fountains'; NH\u2082OH is a more reactive nitrogen nucleophile than NH\u2083; polymerization of products also observed (free amino acid:polymer ratio ~1:3 at 60\u00b0C)\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Hydroxylamine (NH\u2082OH) attacks the carbonyl carbon of \u03b1-ketoisovalerate, forming an oxime intermediate (C=NOH). Under the high-pressure CO\u2082/H\u2082O conditions, the oxime undergoes reduction (facilitated by the reducing environment) and rearrangement to form the \u03b1-amino acid valine. Alternatively, the oxime can undergo a Beckmann-type rearrangement and hydrolysis to yield the amino acid. The supercritical CO\u2082 phase creates a unique reaction environment that promotes both monomer formation and subsequent polymerization.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Synthesis experiments using supercritical CO\u2082/liquid H\u2082O systems simulating 'crust soda fountains' have produced amino acids from hydroxylamine and keto acids at 60\u00b0C. The literature reports that alanine and glycine were detected, with valine identified as a likely product in expanded keto acid trials. These systems also promote polymer formation with a ~1:3 ratio of free amino acids to polymers. This pathway represents an alternative amination route distinct from both Ni-catalyzed reductive amination (rxn_005) and Strecker synthesis.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal protometabolic pathway: CO\u2082 \u2192 pyruvate \u2192 acetolactate \u2192 \u03b1-ketoisovalerate \u2192 valine (Ni reductive amination)\",\n      \"description\": \"Complete hydrothermal route mimicking the biological branched-chain amino acid biosynthetic pathway. CO\u2082 is fixed to pyruvate on greigite/magnetite, two pyruvates condense to acetolactate on pyrite, acetolactate rearranges to \u03b1-ketoisovalerate, and Ni nanoparticles catalyze reductive amination to valine with ~50% yield under serpentinizing vent conditions (80\u00b0C, pH 11, 5 bar H\u2082).\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal FTT + Surface Strecker pathway\",\n      \"description\": \"Isobutyraldehyde is generated by Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis on magnetite in hydrothermal vents, then transported to surface environments where it undergoes Strecker synthesis with NH\u2083 and HCN on montmorillonite clay, followed by sequential nitrile hydrolysis to valine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic direct aminonitrile pathway (Sutherland-Patel)\",\n      \"description\": \"HCN is UV-reduced to acetaldehyde via H\u2082S-driven cyanosulfidic photochemistry with Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox cycling. Acetaldehyde then undergoes iterative HCN additions and reductions to build the branched C\u2085 aminonitrile (valine nitrile) directly, followed by two-step hydrolysis to valine. This systems chemistry approach produces diverse biomolecule precursors simultaneously.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic aldehyde + Strecker combination\",\n      \"description\": \"Cyanosulfidic photochemistry generates both acetaldehyde and then isobutyraldehyde via reductive chain extension. The isobutyraldehyde then enters the classical Strecker pathway with NH\u2083 and HCN on clay surfaces. This pathway links cyanosulfidic C\u2013C bond construction to classical Strecker aminonitrile formation.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal protometabolic + hydroxylamine amination\",\n      \"description\": \"The \u03b1-ketoisovalerate produced by the protometabolic hydrothermal pathway (CO\u2082 \u2192 pyruvate \u2192 acetolactate \u2192 \u03b1-KIV) is aminated by hydroxylamine (generated by UV photolysis of NH\u2083 on TiO\u2082) under supercritical CO\u2082 conditions, bypassing the need for Ni catalyst and H\u2082 pressure.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"FTT aldehyde \u2192 cyanohydrin \u2192 \u03b1-keto acid \u2192 Ni reductive amination\",\n      \"description\": \"Isobutyraldehyde from hydrothermal FTT synthesis undergoes cyanohydrin formation with HCN on the surface, hydrolysis/UV oxidation to \u03b1-ketoisovalerate on TiO\u2082, and then returns to hydrothermal vent conditions for Ni-catalyzed reductive amination to valine. This pathway bridges the isobutyraldehyde and \u03b1-ketoisovalerate hubs.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_005\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_016\", \"mol_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic aldehyde \u2192 cyanohydrin \u2192 \u03b1-keto acid \u2192 Ni reductive amination\",\n      \"description\": \"Full surface-to-hydrothermal pathway: HCN is photoreduced to acetaldehyde, then extended to isobutyraldehyde via cyanosulfidic chemistry. The isobutyraldehyde undergoes cyanohydrin formation and oxidation to \u03b1-ketoisovalerate on the surface, which is then aminated to valine by Ni catalysis in hydrothermal vents.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_005\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_016\", \"mol_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"FTT aldehyde \u2192 cyanohydrin \u2192 \u03b1-keto acid \u2192 hydroxylamine amination\",\n      \"description\": \"Isobutyraldehyde from FTT is converted to \u03b1-ketoisovalerate via the cyanohydrin route (rxn_012 \u2192 rxn_013), then aminated by hydroxylamine under supercritical CO\u2082 conditions. Hydroxylamine is independently generated by UV photolysis of NH\u2083 (rxn_014). All surface/biochemical steps after initial hydrothermal FTT.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_016\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic aldehyde \u2192 cyanohydrin \u2192 \u03b1-keto acid \u2192 hydroxylamine amination\",\n      \"description\": \"Entirely surface-based origin of valine: HCN-derived acetaldehyde is extended to isobutyraldehyde, converted to \u03b1-ketoisovalerate via cyanohydrin hydrolysis/oxidation, and aminated by UV-generated hydroxylamine. No hydrothermal steps required\u2014demonstrating that surface geochemistry alone can produce valine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_016\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Convergent multi-environment pathway through dual \u03b1-ketoisovalerate sources\",\n      \"description\": \"Demonstrates the convergence of hydrothermal and surface chemistry at the \u03b1-ketoisovalerate hub. Two independent routes produce \u03b1-KIV: (1) hydrothermal pyruvate condensation (rxn_001 \u2192 rxn_003 \u2192 rxn_004) and (2) surface cyanohydrin oxidation of FTT-derived isobutyraldehyde (rxn_002 \u2192 rxn_012 \u2192 rxn_013). Both converge at \u03b1-KIV, which is then aminated by the highest-yield Ni reductive amination (rxn_005). This represents the most geochemically robust route due to multiple independent upstream supply chains.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_005\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_016\", \"mol_009\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"description\": \"\u03b1-Ketoisovalerate is the primary convergence hub, reached by two independent pathways: (1) hydrothermal pyruvate \u2192 acetolactate \u2192 \u03b1-KIV, and (2) surface isobutyraldehyde \u2192 cyanohydrin \u2192 \u03b1-KIV. It feeds into two distinct amination routes.\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"description\": \"Valine nitrile is the secondary convergence hub, reached by two independent pathways: (1) Strecker synthesis from isobutyraldehyde (rxn_009), and (2) cyanosulfidic iterative homologation from acetaldehyde (rxn_007). It feeds into hydrolysis to valine.\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_009\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"description\": \"Isobutyraldehyde is a key branch-point hub produced by two routes: (1) hydrothermal FTT synthesis (rxn_002) and (2) surface cyanosulfidic chain extension (rxn_008). It feeds into three downstream reactions: Strecker (rxn_009), cyanohydrin formation (rxn_012), and pantetheine synthesis (not in network). This molecule also connects valine synthesis to cofactor (CoA) synthesis.\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_008\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_009\", \"rxn_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"description\": \"Valine itself is the target convergence point, produced by three independent final reactions: (1) Ni-catalyzed reductive amination (rxn_005), (2) amide hydrolysis from Strecker/cyanosulfidic routes (rxn_011), and (3) hydroxylamine amination (rxn_015).\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_015\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": []\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "Valine", "overall_strategy": "A multi-environment prebiotic synthesis network for valine (2-amino-3-methylpentanoic acid) centered on four hub molecules: pyruvate, \u03b1-ketoisovalerate, isobutyraldehyde, and valine nitrile. The network integrates (1) hydrothermal CO\u2082 fixation to pyruvate and Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis of isobutyraldehyde, (2) surface cyanosulfidic photochemistry producing acetaldehyde and building branched C\u2084\u2013C\u2085 intermediates via iterative HCN reductive homologation, and (3) biochemical assembly via Strecker hydrolysis and Ni-catalyzed reductive amination. Two major convergence points\u2014\u03b1-ketoisovalerate (reached from both pyruvate condensation and cyanohydrin hydrolysis of isobutyraldehyde) and valine nitrile (reached from both Strecker synthesis and cyanosulfidic iterative homologation)\u2014create a densely interconnected and redundant network. Literature-cited high-yield pathways include Ni-catalyzed reductive amination (~50% yield, Kaur et al.), Strecker synthesis from isobutyraldehyde (Miller re-analyses), and Sutherland cyanosulfidic photochemistry with Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox cycling.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "Carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "Hydrogen gas", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "ammonia", "common_name": "Ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "HCN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "Hydrogen cyanide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "H2S", "iupac_name": "hydrogen sulfide", "common_name": "Hydrogen sulfide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2S/h1H2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "H2O", "iupac_name": "water", "common_name": "Water", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "C3H4O3", "iupac_name": "2-oxopropanoic acid", "common_name": "Pyruvate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "C5H8O4", "iupac_name": "2-acetyl-2-hydroxypropanoic acid", "common_name": "Acetolactate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H8O4/c1-3(6)5(2,9)4(7)8/h9H,1-2H3,(H,7,8)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "C5H8O3", "iupac_name": "3-methyl-2-oxobutanoic acid", "common_name": "\u03b1-Ketoisovalerate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H8O3/c1-3(2)4(6)5(7)8/h3H,1-2H3,(H,7,8)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C4H8O", "iupac_name": "2-methylpropanal", "common_name": "Isobutyraldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H8O/c1-3(2)4-5/h3-4H,1-2H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C5H10N2", "iupac_name": "2-amino-3-methylbutanenitrile", "common_name": "Valine nitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H10N2/c1-3(2)4(6)5-7/h3-4H,6H2,1-2H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C5H10N2O", "iupac_name": "2-amino-3-methylbutanamide", "common_name": "Valine amide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H12N2O/c1-3(2)4(6)5(7)8/h3-4H,6H2,1-2H3,(H2,7,8)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "C5H11NO2", "iupac_name": "2-amino-3-methylbutanoic acid", "common_name": "Valine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H11NO2/c1-3(2)4(6)5(7)8/h3-4H,6H2,1-2H3,(H,7,8)", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C2H4O", "iupac_name": "acetaldehyde", "common_name": "Acetaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O/c1-2-3/h2H,1H3", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "NH3O", "iupac_name": "hydroxylamine", "common_name": "Hydroxylamine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3NO/c1-2/h2H,1H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_016", "formula": "C5H9NO", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxy-3-methylbutanenitrile", "common_name": "Isobutyraldehyde cyanohydrin", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H9NO/c1-3(2)4(7)5-6/h3-4,7H,1-2H3", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "Hydrothermal CO\u2082 reduction to pyruvate on iron-sulfur minerals", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_007"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)", "magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (50-200 bar)", "catalyst": "greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084) and magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Alkaline pH 9-11, serpentinization-derived H\u2082, net reaction: 3CO\u2082 + 5H\u2082 \u2192 pyruvate + 4H\u2082O; proceeds via formate and acetyl intermediates on mineral surfaces"}, "mechanism": "Multi-step reductive fixation of CO\u2082 on Fe\u2083S\u2084/Fe\u2083O\u2084 surfaces. CO\u2082 is first reduced to formate via surface-bound hydride transfer, then to CO/formyl intermediates. Sequential C\u2013C coupling on the mineral surface produces a C\u2083 \u03b1-keto acid. The greigite surface acts as an analog of biological [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters, facilitating the reductive carboxylation of thioacetate intermediates to pyruvate, analogous to the Wood-Ljungdahl pathway.", "reasoning": "Greigite and pyrrhotite have been shown to catalyze the reductive carboxylation of thioacetate to pyruvate, a central step in the Wood-Ljungdahl pathway analog (Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user, 1997; Cody et al., 2000). CO\u2082 hydrogenation to formate on greigite at 100\u00b0C has been demonstrated experimentally. Pyruvate is the central metabolic hub of the network and a key precursor to \u03b1-keto acids including \u03b1-ketoisovalerate. The iron-sulfur world theory (W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user, 1988) provides the theoretical framework."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis of isobutyraldehyde on magnetite", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "400-500K", "pressure": "high (100-500 bar)", "catalyst": "magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Fischer-Tropsch-type conditions with CO\u2082 first reduced to CO; branched aldehyde is a minor but confirmed product alongside linear alcohols, aldehydes, and hydrocarbons"}, "mechanism": "CO\u2082 is first reduced to CO on magnetite surfaces via the reverse water-gas shift reaction. CO then undergoes chain growth via methylene insertion on the Fe\u2083O\u2084 surface. The branched C\u2084 aldehyde (isobutyraldehyde, 2-methylpropanal) forms as a minor product when chain growth includes a methyl-branching step. Surface-bound carbene intermediates insert into growing alkyl chains, with branching favored at specific surface sites.", "reasoning": "Fischer-Tropsch-type (FTT) synthesis on magnetite in submarine hydrothermal systems has been demonstrated to produce C\u2081\u2013C\u2083\u2085 hydrocarbons, alcohols, and aldehydes (McCollom et al., 1999; Rushdi & Simoneit, 2001). While selectivity for isobutyraldehyde specifically is low and the literature notes that 'the prebiotic synthesis of isobutyraldehyde in high concentrations is less understood,' FTT remains the most plausible hydrothermal source of branched C\u2084 aldehydes. Isobutyraldehyde is a critical precursor both for valine via Strecker synthesis and for pantetheine/CoA via the Powner pathway."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Pyruvate condensation to acetolactate on pyrite surface", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_008", "mol_001"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS\u2082)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (50-200 bar)", "catalyst": "pyrite (FeS\u2082)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Alkaline pH 9-11; analogous to biological acetolactate synthase; one pyruvate undergoes decarboxylation to form a C\u2082 carbanion equivalent (hydroxyethyl-TPP analog) that attacks the second pyruvate"}, "mechanism": "One molecule of pyruvate undergoes surface-catalyzed decarboxylation on pyrite, generating a reactive C\u2082 carbanion (an acetaldehyde equivalent or 'active acetaldehyde' bound to the mineral surface). This nucleophilic C\u2082 unit attacks the carbonyl carbon of a second pyruvate molecule, forming 2-acetolactate (2-acetyl-2-hydroxypropanoic acid) with release of CO\u2082. The mineral surface stabilizes the carbanion intermediate and provides a confined reaction environment.", "reasoning": "This reaction is the prebiotic analog of the first step in the biological branched-chain amino acid biosynthetic pathway catalyzed by acetolactate synthase (AHAS). Pyrite surfaces have been shown to catalyze decarboxylation and C\u2013C bond formation reactions (Cody et al., 2000, 2004). The iron-sulfur surface acts as a primitive cofactor, stabilizing the reactive intermediates. This condensation provides the critical C\u2085 skeleton required for valine biosynthesis. Similar aldol-type condensations on mineral surfaces have been demonstrated in hydrothermal analog experiments."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Rearrangement-reduction of acetolactate to \u03b1-ketoisovalerate", "inputs": ["mol_008"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)", "elemental nickel (Ni\u2070)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (50-200 bar)", "catalyst": "greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084) with trace Ni", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Alkaline pH 9-11; proceeds via acid-catalyzed 1,2-alkyl migration followed by reduction; may also involve partial dehydration-rehydration on mineral surface; analogous to biological ketol-acid reductoisomerase"}, "mechanism": "Acetolactate undergoes a 1,2-alkyl shift (pinacol-type rearrangement) to form 3-methyl-2-oxobutanoic acid (\u03b1-ketoisovalerate). On the greigite surface, the hydroxyl group of acetolactate is activated, facilitating the migration of the methyl-bearing carbon. The resulting intermediate may be further reduced/oxidized to yield the stable \u03b1-keto acid. Ni traces in the greigite lattice enhance the rearrangement by providing Lewis acid sites.", "reasoning": "In biological systems, acetolactate is converted to \u03b1-ketoisovalerate by ketol-acid reductoisomerase (KARI) in a two-step reaction involving an alkyl migration and NADPH-dependent reduction. Prebiotic analogs on mineral surfaces are plausible, as iron-sulfur minerals can catalyze similar rearrangements. The role of Ni in promoting rearrangement reactions on sulfide minerals has been noted in the context of the iron-nickel-sulfur world (Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user, 1997). This step is essential for converting the linear acetolactate skeleton into the branched \u03b1-ketoisovalerate required for valine."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Nickel-catalyzed reductive amination of \u03b1-ketoisovalerate to valine", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_003", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_013", "mol_006"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["elemental nickel (Ni\u2070)", "greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "353K (80\u00b0C)", "pressure": "5 bar H\u2082", "catalyst": "Ni\u2070 nanoparticles", "aqueous": "true", "other": "pH 11, alkaline conditions, 72 hours reaction time, NH\u2084\u207a/NH\u2083 concentration >5 mM; highly selective for amino acid over alcohol product when sufficient ammonia present"}, "mechanism": "The carbonyl of \u03b1-ketoisovalerate reacts with ammonia to form an imine (Schiff base) intermediate. The imine is then reduced by H\u2082 activated on the Ni\u2070 nanoparticle surface, yielding valine. The Ni surface activates molecular hydrogen via heterolytic cleavage, generating surface-bound hydride that reduces the C=N bond stereoselectively. At pH 11, ammonia is the predominant nitrogen nucleophile.", "reasoning": "Kaur et al. demonstrated that Ni nanoparticles catalyze the reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids with ~50% yield for branched-chain amino acids including valine under conditions mimicking serpentinizing alkaline vents (80\u00b0C, pH 11, 5 bar H\u2082, 72 hours). The reaction is highly selective for the amino acid over the corresponding alcohol (isobutanol) when sufficient ammonia is present. H\u2082 is produced in vast quantities during serpentinization of olivine, making this pathway thermodynamically and geochemically robust. This represents the highest-yield experimentally validated prebiotic route to valine."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Cyanosulfidic UV-driven reduction of HCN to acetaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_004", "mol_005", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["stibnite (Sb\u2082S\u2083)", "TiO\u2082 (anatase)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-320K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox ions", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV irradiation (\u03bb < 300 nm, young Sun); H\u2082S serves as stoichiometric reductant; Cu ions cycle between +1 and +2 oxidation states to mediate electron transfer; neutral pH buffered by phosphate"}, "mechanism": "HCN undergoes UV-driven photoreduction in the presence of H\u2082S as the sacrificial electron donor. Cu(I) is photooxidized to Cu(II), with the released electron reducing HCN to formaldehyde imine (formaldimine, CH\u2082=NH) or formaldehyde. Cu(II) is re-reduced to Cu(I) by H\u2082S, depositing elemental sulfur. Two equivalents of the C\u2081 reduced products undergo Cu-mediated reductive coupling to form acetaldehyde (C\u2082). The sulfide mineral surface (stibnite) stabilizes Cu species and provides additional photocatalytic activity.", "reasoning": "The Sutherland group demonstrated that HCN and its derivatives undergo UV-driven reductive homologation in the presence of H\u2082S, producing a cascade of reduced carbon species including aldehydes (Patel et al., 2015; Ritson & Sutherland, 2012). Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox cycling is central to this cyanosulfidic network. The literature identifies acetaldehyde and glycolaldehyde as key C\u2082 intermediates formed in this process. TiO\u2082 (anatase) on early Earth volcanic surfaces would have provided additional UV photocatalytic capability. Stibnite is identified as a relevant sulfide mineral for cyanosulfidic chemistry."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Cyanosulfidic iterative reductive homologation to valine nitrile", "inputs": ["mol_014", "mol_004", "mol_005", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["stibnite (Sb\u2082S\u2083)", "TiO\u2082 (anatase)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-320K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox ions", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV irradiation (\u03bb < 300 nm); multi-step iterative process: acetaldehyde undergoes sequential HCN addition, UV-driven H\u2082S reduction, and amination to build the branched C\u2085 aminonitrile; neutral pH with phosphate buffering; involves at least 2\u20133 iterative addition-reduction cycles"}, "mechanism": "Step 1: Acetaldehyde undergoes nucleophilic addition of HCN to form lactonitrile (acetaldehyde cyanohydrin, C\u2083). Step 2: The nitrile is reduced by H\u2082S under UV/Cu photoredox conditions to form an aminol or aldehyde (C\u2083 reduced species including propanal). Step 3: Further HCN addition to the C\u2083 aldehyde/imine, followed by reductive branching step involving methyl transfer or \u03b2-branching, yields the C\u2085 branched aminonitrile, 2-amino-3-methylbutanenitrile (valine nitrile). The branching selectivity arises from the thermodynamic stability of the isopropyl configuration and the steric environment of the Cu-catalyzed reduction step.", "reasoning": "The Sutherland-Patel cyanosulfidic network demonstrates that valine's precursor 2-amino-3-methylbutanenitrile is 'formed through a sequence of iterative HCN additions and reductions' using HCN, H\u2082S, and UV light with Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox (Patel et al., 2015). This multi-step process generates diverse amino acid nitriles simultaneously. The exact intermediates in each iterative cycle are not all fully characterized, but the overall transformation from C\u2082 aldehyde to C\u2085 branched aminonitrile via 2\u20133 homologation cycles is established. This pathway is notable for producing amino acid, nucleotide, and lipid precursors from a common feedstock."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Cyanosulfidic reductive chain extension to isobutyraldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_014", "mol_004", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["stibnite (Sb\u2082S\u2083)", "TiO\u2082 (anatase)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-320K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox ions", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV irradiation (\u03bb < 300 nm); H\u2082S is reductant; similar iterative reductive homologation as rxn_007 but stopping at the C\u2084 aldehyde stage before amination; branched aldehyde product"}, "mechanism": "Acetaldehyde undergoes HCN addition to form lactonitrile (C\u2083). Under UV/Cu photoredox conditions with H\u2082S as reductant, the nitrile is reduced to a C\u2083 aldehyde (propanal or methylformaldehyde). A further HCN addition and reduction cycle extends the chain with branching, yielding the C\u2084 branched aldehyde isobutyraldehyde (2-methylpropanal). The branching pattern arises from reductive methylation during the chain extension process. This represents the aldehyde branch of the cyanosulfidic network, producing the Strecker precursor for valine.", "reasoning": "The cyanosulfidic reductive homologation network (Sutherland and colleagues) produces both aldehydes and aminonitriles depending on the stage at which amination occurs. Isobutyraldehyde is identified in the literature as 'the specific precursor required for valine' in Strecker synthesis and is also 'directly involved in the synthesis of universal cofactors like pantetheine' (Powner et al.). The Powner group demonstrated that isobutyraldehyde selectively reacts within complex cyanosulfidic mixtures to form pantetheine, linking valine precursors to cofactor synthesis. Generating isobutyraldehyde via cyanosulfidic reduction provides a surface-environment source complementary to hydrothermal FTT."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Strecker synthesis: isobutyraldehyde to valine nitrile", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_003", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_011", "mol_006"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite clay surface", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Aqueous phase; NH\u2083 and HCN in solution; clay surface concentrates reactants via adsorption; neutral to slightly alkaline pH; room temperature to 370K; effective in dilute solution due to clay concentration effect"}, "mechanism": "Step 1: Isobutyraldehyde reacts with ammonia to form an imine (Schiff base), (CH\u2083)\u2082CHCH=NH, with loss of water. Step 2: Cyanide ion (CN\u207b) acts as a nucleophile, attacking the electrophilic carbon of the imine to form 2-amino-3-methylbutanenitrile (valine nitrile). The montmorillonite surface adsorbs and concentrates the aldehyde and amine reactants in its interlayer spaces, increasing effective concentration and promoting the condensation.", "reasoning": "The Strecker synthesis is the primary identified pathway for valine formation in Miller-type spark discharge experiments (Miller, 1953, 1957; Johnson et al., 2008 re-analysis). Isobutyraldehyde reacts with NH\u2083 and HCN in the aqueous phase to form valine nitrile. Re-analysis of Miller's archived samples by LC-ToF-MS confirmed valine among the products. Montmorillonite clay is well-established as a prebiotic catalyst that concentrates organics from dilute solutions (Bernal, 1951; Ferris et al., 1996). The Strecker mechanism for branched amino acids is thermodynamically favorable, with formic acid further lowering barriers for amination (computational studies showing barrier reduction from 22.7 to 13.7 kcal/mol with HCOOH)."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Hydrolysis of valine nitrile to valine amide", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "Slightly acidic to neutral pH (pH 4-7) promotes nitrile hydrolysis; formic acid can significantly lower the activation barrier from 23.2 to 9.3 kcal/mol; slow at neutral pH, accelerated by mild heating or acid catalysis"}, "mechanism": "Water acts as a nucleophile attacking the electrophilic carbon of the nitrile group (C\u2261N). A tetrahedral intermediate forms, which collapses to release ammonia-equivalent and form the amide bond. The reaction proceeds: R-C\u2261N + H\u2082O \u2192 R-C(=O)NH\u2082. Formic acid, when present as a catalytic proton shuttle, dramatically lowers the activation barrier by facilitating proton transfer in the transition state.", "reasoning": "Nitrile hydrolysis to amide is the first step in the two-step conversion of Strecker aminonitriles to amino acids. Computational studies (using RTIP sampling) show that formic acid reduces the hydration barrier from 23.2 to 9.3 kcal/mol, making this step kinetically accessible under mild prebiotic conditions. Formic acid is abundantly produced in hydrothermal CO\u2082 reduction (rxn_001 products), providing a natural catalyst for this step. The reaction is well-characterized in the context of Miller-Urey chemistry and Strecker synthesis (Miller, 1957; Cleaves et al., 2008)."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Hydrolysis of valine amide to valine", "inputs": ["mol_012", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_013", "mol_003"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "Acidic or alkaline conditions accelerate hydrolysis; pH < 4 or pH > 10 optimal; proceeds slowly at neutral pH over days to weeks; thermal acceleration at 350-370K"}, "mechanism": "The amide undergoes nucleophilic addition of water (or hydroxide at high pH) to the carbonyl carbon of the amide group, forming a tetrahedral intermediate. Collapse of this intermediate releases ammonia and yields the free carboxylic acid, producing valine (2-amino-3-methylbutanoic acid). Under acidic conditions, the amide nitrogen is protonated to form a better leaving group.", "reasoning": "Amide hydrolysis to carboxylic acid is the final step of the classical Strecker amino acid synthesis. This reaction is well-established in prebiotic chemistry literature (Miller, 1957; Schlesinger & Miller, 1983). In prebiotic pools, cycles of pH change (e.g., mixing of alkaline vent fluids with acidic ocean water) would periodically accelerate this hydrolysis. The reaction is thermodynamically favorable (\u0394G < 0) in aqueous solution and proceeds to completion over timescales of days to weeks under mildly acidic conditions."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Cyanohydrin formation from isobutyraldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_016"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite concentrates reactants", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Slightly alkaline pH favors CN\u207b formation; rapid equilibrium reaction; cyanohydrin is kinetically accessible intermediate; competes with Strecker imine pathway depending on NH\u2083 availability"}, "mechanism": "In the absence of sufficient ammonia, or when CN\u207b attacks the aldehyde directly before imine formation, isobutyraldehyde undergoes nucleophilic addition of cyanide to the carbonyl carbon, forming 2-hydroxy-3-methylbutanenitrile (the cyanohydrin). This reaction is rapid and reversible, with the equilibrium favoring product formation at pH 8-9 where CN\u207b concentration is significant.", "reasoning": "Cyanohydrin formation from aldehydes and HCN is one of the most fundamental reactions in prebiotic chemistry. It represents the alternative branch point from isobutyraldehyde: when NH\u2083 is present, Strecker aminonitrile forms (rxn_009); when NH\u2083 is absent or at low concentration, the cyanohydrin forms instead. This provides a route from the aldehyde hub to the \u03b1-keto acid hub via hydrolysis and oxidation (rxn_013). Cyanohydrin chemistry is well-established in the prebiotic literature as a source of \u03b1-hydroxy acids, which are abundant in meteorites alongside amino acids (Peltzer & Bada, 1978)."}, {"id": "rxn_013", "name": "Hydrolysis and UV oxidation of cyanohydrin to \u03b1-ketoisovalerate", "inputs": ["mol_016", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO\u2082 (anatase)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO\u2082 photocatalyst for oxidation step", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Two-step process: (1) nitrile hydrolysis to \u03b1-hydroxyisovaleric acid (300-350K, mild acid/base, days); (2) UV-driven oxidation of \u03b1-hydroxy acid to \u03b1-keto acid on TiO\u2082 surface (\u03bb < 350 nm); net: cyanohydrin \u2192 \u03b1-hydroxyisovaleric acid \u2192 \u03b1-ketoisovalerate"}, "mechanism": "Step 1 (Hydrolysis): The nitrile group of 2-hydroxy-3-methylbutanenitrile undergoes hydrolysis (nitrile \u2192 amide \u2192 acid), yielding 2-hydroxy-3-methylbutanoic acid (\u03b1-hydroxyisovaleric acid). Step 2 (Oxidation): The \u03b1-hydroxy acid is oxidized at the \u03b1-carbon by UV light on TiO\u2082 photocatalytic surfaces, converting the \u2013CHOH\u2013 group to \u2013CO\u2013 and yielding 3-methyl-2-oxobutanoic acid (\u03b1-ketoisovalerate). TiO\u2082 generates reactive oxygen species under UV that selectively oxidize \u03b1-hydroxy acids.", "reasoning": "\u03b1-Hydroxy acids are found alongside amino acids in carbonaceous chondrites, confirming their prebiotic relevance (Peltzer & Bada, 1978; Pizzarello et al., 2004). The hydrolysis of cyanohydrins to \u03b1-hydroxy acids is well-established. Subsequent oxidation to \u03b1-keto acids on TiO\u2082 photocatalytic surfaces is plausible given the abundance of TiO\u2082 (anatase/rutile) on early Earth volcanic terrain. This reaction provides a critical bridge between the isobutyraldehyde hub and the \u03b1-ketoisovalerate hub, connecting FTT and cyanosulfidic aldehyde pathways to the reductive amination route. This topology was identified as missing in the previous network attempt."}, {"id": "rxn_014", "name": "UV photolysis of ammonia to hydroxylamine", "inputs": ["mol_003", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO\u2082 (anatase)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "280-320K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO\u2082 photocatalyst", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV irradiation \u03bb < 230 nm (strong UV flux on early Earth without ozone layer); low yield but continuous production; NH\u2083 + h\u03bd \u2192 NH\u2082\u2022 + H\u2022; NH\u2082\u2022 + OH\u2022 \u2192 NH\u2082OH; TiO\u2082 enhances photolysis rate"}, "mechanism": "UV photons (\u03bb < 230 nm) homolytically cleave the N\u2013H bond of ammonia, generating amidogen radical (NH\u2082\u2022) and hydrogen radical (H\u2022). Simultaneously, UV photolysis of water generates hydroxyl radical (OH\u2022). Radical recombination of NH\u2082\u2022 and OH\u2022 yields hydroxylamine (NH\u2082OH). TiO\u2082 surfaces enhance the process by generating reactive radical species via photocatalytic water splitting.", "reasoning": "UV photolysis of NH\u2083 in aqueous solution to produce hydroxylamine is a known photochemical reaction. On early Earth, the absence of an ozone layer allowed deep UV (< 230 nm) to reach the surface. The literature identifies hydroxylamine as a reactive nitrogen species for amino acid synthesis in supercritical CO\u2082/H\u2082O systems. TiO\u2082 (anatase) is an effective UV photocatalyst found in volcanic terrain. While yields are low per photon, continuous UV exposure over geological timescales provides a steady supply of NH\u2082OH."}, {"id": "rxn_015", "name": "Hydroxylamine amination of \u03b1-ketoisovalerate to valine", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_015"], "outputs": ["mol_013", "mol_006"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "333K (60\u00b0C)", "pressure": "high (supercritical CO\u2082, >74 bar)", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "Supercritical CO\u2082/liquid H\u2082O biphasic system mimicking 'crust soda fountains'; NH\u2082OH is a more reactive nitrogen nucleophile than NH\u2083; polymerization of products also observed (free amino acid:polymer ratio ~1:3 at 60\u00b0C)"}, "mechanism": "Hydroxylamine (NH\u2082OH) attacks the carbonyl carbon of \u03b1-ketoisovalerate, forming an oxime intermediate (C=NOH). Under the high-pressure CO\u2082/H\u2082O conditions, the oxime undergoes reduction (facilitated by the reducing environment) and rearrangement to form the \u03b1-amino acid valine. Alternatively, the oxime can undergo a Beckmann-type rearrangement and hydrolysis to yield the amino acid. The supercritical CO\u2082 phase creates a unique reaction environment that promotes both monomer formation and subsequent polymerization.", "reasoning": "Synthesis experiments using supercritical CO\u2082/liquid H\u2082O systems simulating 'crust soda fountains' have produced amino acids from hydroxylamine and keto acids at 60\u00b0C. The literature reports that alanine and glycine were detected, with valine identified as a likely product in expanded keto acid trials. These systems also promote polymer formation with a ~1:3 ratio of free amino acids to polymers. This pathway represents an alternative amination route distinct from both Ni-catalyzed reductive amination (rxn_005) and Strecker synthesis."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Hydrothermal protometabolic pathway: CO\u2082 \u2192 pyruvate \u2192 acetolactate \u2192 \u03b1-ketoisovalerate \u2192 valine (Ni reductive amination)", "description": "Complete hydrothermal route mimicking the biological branched-chain amino acid biosynthetic pathway. CO\u2082 is fixed to pyruvate on greigite/magnetite, two pyruvates condense to acetolactate on pyrite, acetolactate rearranges to \u03b1-ketoisovalerate, and Ni nanoparticles catalyze reductive amination to valine with ~50% yield under serpentinizing vent conditions (80\u00b0C, pH 11, 5 bar H\u2082).", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_005"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_008", "mol_009"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "name": "Hydrothermal FTT + Surface Strecker pathway", "description": "Isobutyraldehyde is generated by Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis on magnetite in hydrothermal vents, then transported to surface environments where it undergoes Strecker synthesis with NH\u2083 and HCN on montmorillonite clay, followed by sequential nitrile hydrolysis to valine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_009", "rxn_010", "rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_010", "mol_011", "mol_012"]}, {"pathway_id": "P3", "name": "Cyanosulfidic direct aminonitrile pathway (Sutherland-Patel)", "description": "HCN is UV-reduced to acetaldehyde via H\u2082S-driven cyanosulfidic photochemistry with Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox cycling. Acetaldehyde then undergoes iterative HCN additions and reductions to build the branched C\u2085 aminonitrile (valine nitrile) directly, followed by two-step hydrolysis to valine. This systems chemistry approach produces diverse biomolecule precursors simultaneously.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_010", "rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_014", "mol_011", "mol_012"]}, {"pathway_id": "P4", "name": "Cyanosulfidic aldehyde + Strecker combination", "description": "Cyanosulfidic photochemistry generates both acetaldehyde and then isobutyraldehyde via reductive chain extension. The isobutyraldehyde then enters the classical Strecker pathway with NH\u2083 and HCN on clay surfaces. This pathway links cyanosulfidic C\u2013C bond construction to classical Strecker aminonitrile formation.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_006", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_010", "rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_014", "mol_010", "mol_011", "mol_012"]}, {"pathway_id": "P5", "name": "Hydrothermal protometabolic + hydroxylamine amination", "description": "The \u03b1-ketoisovalerate produced by the protometabolic hydrothermal pathway (CO\u2082 \u2192 pyruvate \u2192 acetolactate \u2192 \u03b1-KIV) is aminated by hydroxylamine (generated by UV photolysis of NH\u2083 on TiO\u2082) under supercritical CO\u2082 conditions, bypassing the need for Ni catalyst and H\u2082 pressure.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_014", "rxn_015"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_008", "mol_009", "mol_015"]}, {"pathway_id": "P6", "name": "FTT aldehyde \u2192 cyanohydrin \u2192 \u03b1-keto acid \u2192 Ni reductive amination", "description": "Isobutyraldehyde from hydrothermal FTT synthesis undergoes cyanohydrin formation with HCN on the surface, hydrolysis/UV oxidation to \u03b1-ketoisovalerate on TiO\u2082, and then returns to hydrothermal vent conditions for Ni-catalyzed reductive amination to valine. This pathway bridges the isobutyraldehyde and \u03b1-ketoisovalerate hubs.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_012", "rxn_013", "rxn_005"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_010", "mol_016", "mol_009"]}, {"pathway_id": "P7", "name": "Cyanosulfidic aldehyde \u2192 cyanohydrin \u2192 \u03b1-keto acid \u2192 Ni reductive amination", "description": "Full surface-to-hydrothermal pathway: HCN is photoreduced to acetaldehyde, then extended to isobutyraldehyde via cyanosulfidic chemistry. The isobutyraldehyde undergoes cyanohydrin formation and oxidation to \u03b1-ketoisovalerate on the surface, which is then aminated to valine by Ni catalysis in hydrothermal vents.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_006", "rxn_008", "rxn_012", "rxn_013", "rxn_005"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_014", "mol_010", "mol_016", "mol_009"]}, {"pathway_id": "P8", "name": "