 and on the anoxic early Earth suitable oxidants are limited (UV, Mn oxides, ferric iron). The Hydrothermal \u2192 Surface \u2192 Hydrothermal progression is unusual but not implausible if products are recycled through vent systems.\",\n            \"approved\": true,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_012\"],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"Specify oxidant for rxn_012: UV photolysis, MnO2, or Fe(III) minerals\", \"Consider whether return to hydrothermal conditions for rxn_013 is geologically plausible\", \"Improve FTT selectivity argument with mineral catalyst specification\"]\n        },\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\"rxn_001\": 0.90, \"rxn_002\": 0.62, \"rxn_003\": 0.70, \"rxn_004\": 0.65, \"rxn_014\": 0.68, \"rxn_015\": 0.68},\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.68,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": 0.75,\n            \"environmental_progression\": 0.75,\n            \"target_achievement\": 0.72,\n            \"overall_confidence\": 0.72,\n            \"feedback\": \"Alternative nitrogen donor route using hydroxylamine. The supercritical CO2 literature supports hydroxylamine amination of keto acids, but the evidence is weaker than for Ni reductive amination. rxn_014 (UV photolysis of NH3 \u2192 NH2OH) is plausible but low-yield. The Hydrothermal \u2192 Surface \u2192 Biochemical progression is good. Shares the rxn_002 weakness of the protometabolic branch.\",\n            \"approved\": false,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\"],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"Strengthen hydroxylamine formation mechanism\", \"Consider alternative NH2OH sources (e.g., NO reduction)\", \"Provide more detail on supercritical CO2 conditions for rxn_015\"]\n        },\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\"rxn_005\": 0.58, \"rxn_010\": 0.90, \"rxn_011\": 0.80, \"rxn_012\": 0.62, \"rxn_014\": 0.68, \"rxn_015\"