etwork design. Key weaknesses: (a) rxn_002 (formate \u2192 pyruvate) skips the critical thioacetate intermediate documented in iron-sulfur protometabolism; (b) rxn_006 (HCN + H2S \u2192 valine nitrile) collapses ~5-6 iterative cyanosulfidic steps into one, omitting UV, Cu catalysis, and phosphate buffering; (c) rxn_012 lacks an oxidant specification; (d) pyridoxamine (mol_018) has no synthesis route in the network; (e) some surface reactions lack mineral catalyst specifications. Despite these issues, the network's convergent architecture and strong anchoring in experimental literature (particularly the Ni reductive amination endpoint) make it a viable and informative model. The network is APPROVED with the recommendation to address the noted gaps in future iterations.\",\n    \"approved\": true,\n    \"hub_quality\": 0.88,\n    \"convergence_quality\": 0.87\n}", "parsed_response": {"pathway_evaluations": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "reaction_scores": {"rxn_001": 0.9, "rxn_002": 0.62, "rxn_003": 0.7, "rxn_004": 0.65, "rxn_013": 0.95}, "chemical_feasibility": 0.74, "pathway_coherence": 0.82, "environmental_progression": 0.72, "target_achievement": 0.9, "overall_confidence": 0.8, "feedback": "Strongest final step (Kaur et al. ~50% Ni-catalyzed reductive amination) is the backbone of this pathway. However, rxn_002 (formate \u2192 pyruvate in one step) is an oversimplification; in literature this typically proceeds through acetyl-CoA/thioacetate intermediates. rxn_003/004 (pyruvate condensation \u2192 acetolactate \u2192 \u03b1-ketoisovalerate) mirror the biological BCAA pathway but prebiotic evidence for this specific rearrangement cascade on pyrite is limited. The entirely hydrothermal environment is internally consistent but limits cross-environment synergy.", "approved": true, "problematic_reactions": ["rxn_002", "rxn_004"], "suggestions": ["Include thioacetate or acetyl thioester intermediate between formate and pyruvate", "Provide more detail on the mineral-catalyzed ace